'''Jennifer Lynn Lopez''' (born July 24, 1969), also known as '''J. Lo''', is an [[United States|American]] singer, actress, dancer, fashion designer, author, and producer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Zach|title=Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony Are Officially Divorced, Nearly 3 Years After Split|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/519856/jennifer-lopez-and-marc-anthony-are-officially-divorced-nearly-3-years-after-split|accessdate=16 August 2014|work=E!|date=June 18, 2014|quote=She also filed paperwork to have her legal name be changed from Jennifer Muniz (Anthony's real surname) back to Jennifer Lopez.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/06/jennifer-lopez-name-change_n_4398985.html |title=Jennifer Lopez Requests Name Change In Divorce Documents |publisher=The Huffington Post |date=2014-01-25 |accessdate=2014-07-20}}</ref>

Lopez became interested in pursuing a career in the entertainment industry following a minor role in the film, ''[[My Little Girl]]'' (1986), to the dismay of her [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] parents, who believed that it was an unrealistic career route for a Hispanic. Lopez gained her first regular high-profile job as a [[List of In Living Color cast members#Fly Girls (house dance troupe)|Fly Girl]] dancer on ''[[In Living Color]]'' in 1991, where she remained a regular until she decided to pursue an acting career in 1993. She received her first leading role in the [[Selena]] biopic [[Selena (film)|of the same name]] in 1997. Lopez became the first Latina actress to earn over {{US$|1{{nbsp}}million|link=yes}} for a role the following year, with the film ''[[Out of Sight]]''. She ventured into the music industry in 1999, with her debut studio album, ''[[On the 6]]'', preceded by the number-one single "[[If You Had My Love]]".

With the simultaneous release of her second studio album ''[[J.Lo (album)|J.Lo]]'' and her film ''[[The Wedding Planner]]'' in 2001, Lopez became the first woman to have a number one album and film in the same week. Her 2002 remix album, ''[[J to tha L–O! The Remixes]]'', became the first in history to debut at number one on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], while her fifth studio album, ''[[Como Ama una Mujer]]'' (2007), received the highest first-week sales for a debut Spanish album in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Lopez's First Spanish-Language Album is an Instant #1 on the Billboard Latin Chart: Como Ama Una Mujer Breaks Records with Highest Sales for an Artist's Debut Spanish-Language Album|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/spanish/jennifer/prweb517033.htm|publisher=[[PRWeb]]|accessdate=August 16, 2016|date=April 6, 2007}}</ref> With past record sales of over 60{{nbsp}}million and a cumulative film gross of over {{US$|2{{nbsp}}billion}}, Lopez is regarded as the most influential Hispanic performer in the United States, as well as its highest paid Latin entertainer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Lopez|url=http://www.mtv.com/artists/jennifer-lopez/|website=''[[MTV]]'' |accessdate=January 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name="hhh" /> Along with [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]] and [[Claudia Leitte]], she recorded "[[We Are One (Ole Ola)]]", which served as the [[FIFA World Cup official songs|official song]] of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cantor-Navas|first=Judy|title=Pitbull's 'We Are One (Ole, Ola)' Featuring Jennifer Lopez, Claudia Leitte Named FIFA'S Official World Cup Song|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/global/5884960/pitbulls-we-are-one-ole-ola-featuring-jennifer-lopez-claudia-leitte|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=April 6, 2014|date=January 23, 2014}}</ref>

Beyond entertainment, Lopez enjoys a highly successful business career, consisting of various clothing lines, accessories, fragrances, [[Nuyorican Productions|a production company]], television shows and a [[Lopez Family Foundation|charitable foundation]] among other ventures. Lopez's personal relationships have attracted worldwide media attention; she has been married three times. Following the breakdown of her first marriage, Lopez dated rapper and entertainment mogul [[Sean Combs]]. Following the breakdown of her second marriage to husband [[Cris Judd]], she had a high profile relationship with actor [[Ben Affleck]], with their planned wedding being cancelled four days before the ceremony. Lopez then wed longtime friend [[Marc Anthony]]; they separated after seven years of marriage. Lopez gave birth to their twins, Emme and Maximilian, in 2008.

==Early life==

Jennifer Lynn Lopez was born on July 24, 1969, in the [[Castle Hill, Bronx|Castle Hill]] neighborhood of [[The Bronx]], New York,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courttv.com/trials/puffy/docs/duty-caps_3.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209202541/http://www.courttv.com/trials/puffy/docs/duty-caps_3.html|archivedate=February 9, 2008|title=Duty Captain's Report|accessdate=October 29, 2006|work=[[Court TV]] |date=January 17, 2001}}</ref> to [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] parents Guadalupe Rodríguez and David Lopez. She has an older sister, Leslie, and a younger sister, [[Lynda Lopez|Lynda]], a journalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com/musica/fotos/mamas_y_mamacitas/64457 |title=Mamás y Mamacitas&nbsp;– Música |publisher=[[Terra Networks]] |accessdate=May 24, 2012|date=May 11, 2007}}</ref> David worked the night shift at the Guardian Insurance Company, before becoming a computer technician at the firm, while Guadalupe was a homemaker. When Lopez was born, the family was living in a small apartment. A few years later, her parents had saved up enough money to be able to purchase a two-story house, which was considered a big deal for the relatively poor family.<ref name="Gallick2003">{{harvnb|Gallick|2003}}</ref> At the age of five, Lopez began taking singing and dancing lessons. She toured New York with her school when she was seven years old. Her parents stressed the importance of work ethic and being able to speak English. They encouraged their three daughters to put on performances at home; singing and dancing in front of each other and their friends so that they would stay "out of trouble".<ref name="atriplethreat">{{cite web|url=http://www.evancarmichael.com/Famous-Entrepreneurs/619/The-Triple-Threat-Jennifer-Lopez-is-Born.html |title=The Triple Threat: Jennifer Lopez is Born |publisher=Evan Carmichael |accessdate=March 23, 2012}}</ref> Lopez spent her entire academic career in Catholic schools, finishing at [[Preston High School (New York City)|Preston High School]].<ref name=tca>Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2004</ref> In school, Lopez did gymnastics, ran track on a national level and was a member of the school's softball team.<ref name=rantrack>{{cite book|last=Parish|first=James-Robert|title=Jennifer Lopez: Actor and Singer|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lh1Y2OK-VdsC&pg=PA129&dq=J-Lo:+The+Secret+Behind+Jennifer+Lopez's+Clib+to+the+Top#v=onepage&q=J-Lo%3A%20The%20Secret%20Behind%20Jennifer%20Lopez's%20Clib%20to%20the%20Top&f=false|isbn=978-0-8160-5832-7|date=November 30, 2005}}</ref> She excelled athletically rather than academically, competing in national track championships.<ref name=atriplethreat /> In 1984, at the age of fifteen, she began dating David Cruz, her first boyfriend.<ref name="Gallick2003"/>

While attending her final year of high school, Lopez learned about a film casting that was seeking several teenage girls for small roles. She auditioned and was cast in ''[[My Little Girl]]'' (1986), a low-budget film co-written and directed by Connie Kaiserman.<ref name="Rovi My Little Girl">{{cite web|first=Eleanor |last=Mannikka |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/my-little-girl-v34075|title=My Little Girl&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |work=[[AllRovi]] |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}{{dead link|date=June 2016}}</ref> Lopez acted as Myra, a young woman at a center for troubled girls. After she finished filming her role in the film, Lopez realized that she wanted to become a "famous movie star". To please her parents, though, she enrolled in [[Baruch College]], only to drop out after one semester. She told her parents about her dream of becoming a movie star, but they insisted that it was a "really stupid" idea and that "no Latinos did that". The differences in opinions led Lopez to move out of their family home and into an apartment in [[Manhattan]]. During this period, Lopez performed in regional productions of the musicals ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar]]'' and ''[[Oklahoma!]]''. From there, she was hired for the chorus in a ''Golden Musicals of Broadway'', which toured Europe for five months. She was unhappy with the role, as she was the only member of the chorus to not have a solo. She later got a job on the show ''Synchronicity'' in Japan, where she acted as a dancer, singer and a choreographer.<ref name="Gallick2003"/>

==Career==

===1991–96: Career beginnings===

Lopez was selected as a backup dancer for the [[New Kids on the Block]] in 1991 and performed with them during their performance of "[[Games (New Kids on the Block song)|Games]]" at the [[American Music Awards of 1991|18th Annual American Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Perricon|first=Kathleen|title=Jennifer Lopez dances with New Kids on the Block in 1991 video clip|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-05-10/entertainment/29547058_1_nkotb-music-video-new-kids|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=June 22, 2012|date=May 10, 2011}}</ref> Shortly after, Lopez gained her first regular high-profile job as a [[Fly Girls (dance troupe)|Fly Girl]] dancer on the television program ''[[In Living Color]]''. She applied for the job after one of the cast members was unavailable to continue with the show. Out of 2,000 applicants, Lopez made it to the finals. She was the runner-up, but eventually received the role when the winner was unable to accept the job. She moved with Cruz to Los Angeles to film the series and remained a regular cast member until 1993 when she decided to pursue a full-time acting career. Prior to leaving the show, Lopez briefly worked as a backup dancer for American recording artist [[Janet Jackson]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Morales|first=Ed|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/may/30/entertainment/ca-42339|title=It's Not La Vida Loca to Her|accessdate=January 30, 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 30, 1999}}</ref> Lopez was set to tour with Jackson on her [[Janet World Tour]] in late 1993, but backed out as she wanted to do her "own thing."<ref>{{cite news|title=Living Single|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gCYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA100&dq=This+Is+Me...+Then+jennifer+lopez+million+copies&hl=en&sa=X&ei=s03xT_70N8z3rAG1hqG1Cg&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=This%20Is%20Me...%20Then%20jennifer%20lopez%20million%20copies&f=false|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |accessdate=July 6, 2012|page=100|date=May 2001}}</ref>

Lopez received her first professional acting gig in the [[direct-to-video]] drama film ''[[Lost in the Wild]]'' (1993), co-starring alongside [[Lindsay Wagner]] and [[Robert Loggia]].<ref name="Rovi Lost in the Wild">{{cite web|first=Sandra |last=Brennan |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/lost-in-the-wild-v160416 |title=Lost in the Wild&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |work=[[AllRovi]] |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}</ref> Later in 1993 Lopez signed a deal with [[CBS]] to co-star in the television series ''[[Second Chances (American TV series)|Second Chances]]''. Lopez received her first major big-screen role in [[Gregory Nava]]'s 1995 drama ''[[My Family (film)|My Family]]'', portraying Young Maria.<ref name="Rovi My Family">{{cite web|first=Matthew |last=Tobey |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/my-family-v133610|title=My Family&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |work=AllRovi  |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}{{dead link|date=June 2016}}</ref> Although her role was uncredited, Lopez received an [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Supporting Female]] nomination for her performance.<ref name="Rovi My Family"/> In November 1995, Lopez starred in ''[[Money Train (film)|Money Train]]'' alongside [[Wesley Snipes]] and [[Woody Harrelson]], as [[New York City Transit Police|New York City transit cops]]. In August 1996, Lopez had a supporting role in the comedy ''[[Jack (1996 film)|Jack]]''.<ref name="Rovi Jack">{{cite web|first=Clarke |last=Fountain |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/jack-v136486 |title=Jack&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}{{dead link|date=June 2016}}</ref>

===1997–99: Breakthrough with ''Selena'' and ''On the 6''===

In February 1997, Lopez starred alongside [[Jack Nicholson]] and [[Stephen Dorff]] in the [[neo-noir]] thriller ''[[Blood and Wine]]''.<ref name="Rovi Blood and Wine">{{cite web|first=Sandra |last=Brennan |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/blood-and-wine-v136830 |title=Blood and Wine&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}{{dead link|date=June 2016}}</ref> Lopez starred as the title role of the [[Selena]] biopic [[Selena (film)|of the same name]] in March.<ref name="Rovi Selena">{{cite web|first=Mark |last=Deming |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/selena-v154769 |title=Selena&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}</ref> Despite having previously worked with the film's director on ''My Family'', Lopez was subjected to an intense auditioning process before she was cast in the film.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=Lopez gets Selena role|newspaper=Dallas Morning News |date=June 14, 1996}}</ref> [[Kenneth Turan]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' stated that even in the "forgettable films" ''Money Train'', and ''Jack'', Lopez's "presence and ability made her seem just one role away from stardom" and with ''Selena'' she's "seized the opportunity and turned in an incandescent presentation that is especially strong during the film's numerous musical numbers". He concluded by calling the film not just a celebration of Selena's life, but also of the actress who portrayed her.<ref name="She's Seen in the Best Light">{{cite news |author=Kenneth Turan |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997-03-21/entertainment/ca-40367_1_selena-quintanilla-perez |title=In the Authorized 'Selena,' She's Seen in the Best Light|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=October 10, 1995 |accessdate=December 10, 2012}}</ref> After filming ''Selena'', Lopez was "really feeling [her] Latin roots" and cut a demo in Spanish.<ref>Mendible, M. (2007). "From bananas to buttocks: the Latina body in popular film and culture". Austin: [[University of Texas Press]]. Retrieved September 4, 2012.</ref> Lopez's manager then sent the song, titled "Vivir Sin Ti" (Living without You), to [[Sony Music Entertainment]]'s [[Work Group]], who showed an interest in signing Lopez. [[Tommy Mottola]], the head of the label suggested to her that she sing in English instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TxIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA27&dq=jennifer+lopez+tommy+Mottola&hl=en&sa=X&ei=wQzwT9uPOJL0rAGXmJmSAg&ved=0CGEQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=jennifer%20lopez%20tommy%20Mottola&f=false |page=27 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]] | volume=119 | issn=0006-2510 | number=5 | title=On the Down Lo |date=February 3, 2007 |accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref>

In April, Lopez starred in the horror film ''[[Anaconda (film)|Anaconda]]'' alongside [[Ice Cube]] and [[Jon Voight]].<ref name="Rovi Anaconda">{{cite web|first=Mark |last=Deming |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/anaconda-v154826 |title=Anaconda&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}</ref> Lopez starred alongside [[Sean Penn]] and [[Billy Bob Thornton]] in the crime film ''[[U Turn (1997 film)|U Turn]]'' in October. The film, which is based on the novel ''Stray Dogs'' by [[John Ridley]], received somewhat positive reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/u-turn |title=U Turn |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=December 10, 2012}}</ref> In June, Lopez starred opposite [[George Clooney]] in ''[[Out of Sight (1998 film)|Out of Sight]]'', [[Steven Soderbergh]]'s adaptation of [[Elmore Leonard]]'s novel of the same name (1996).<ref name="Rovi Out of Sight">{{cite web|first=Bhob |last=Stewart |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/out-of-sight-v162749 |title=Out of Sight&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}</ref> Cast as a deputy federal marshal who falls for a charming criminal, Lopez won rave reviews for her performance and became the first Latina actress to earn over $1 million for a role.<ref name="nydailynews1998">{{cite news|last=Kehr|first=Dave|title=Clooney & Lopez Are Lovable At First 'Sight' George Plays A Bank Robber Who Steals Jennifer's Heart|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/clooney-lopez-lovable-sight-george-plays-bank-robber-steals-jennifer-heart-article-1.802614|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6HmBwDxi5 |archivedate=July 1, 2013|work=[[New York Daily News]] |accessdate=January 30, 2012|date=June 26, 1998}}</ref> Lopez provided the voice of Azteca in the computer-animated film ''[[Antz]]'' in October.<ref name="Rovi Antz">{{cite web|first=Bhob |last=Stewart |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/antz-v173454 |title=Antz&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}</ref>

Lopez's debut single, "[[If You Had My Love]]", was released in May 1999, as she began to ready her first album.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jennifer Lopez Readies First Album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date=April 15, 1999 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=20010130&id=0cYvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PzUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1737,9846654|title=Jennifer Lopez release proves to be a good Latin-soul album|author=Brian McCollum|newspaper=[[Rome News-Tribune]] |date=January 30, 2001|accessdate=January 15, 2010}}</ref> Lopez became the first artist to top the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 with their debut single since [[Britney Spears]] did so with her single, "[[...Baby One More Time (song)|...Baby One More Time]]", four months prior.<ref name="billboardno1issue">{{cite book|title=Billboard Magazine Vol. 111, No. 24|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uw0EAAAAMBAJ&source=gbs_all_issues_r&cad=1|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|accessdate=July 2, 2012|page=90|date=June 12, 1999}}</ref> During production of her debut album ''[[On the 6]]'', Lopez was aware that she received her recording contract on the premise of her looks and having an already established name in the entertainment industry, and wanted to prove she had musical talent.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1ZGMcUEvkyEC&pg=PA104 |title=Alicia Keys, Ashanti, Beyoncé, Destiny's Child, Jennifer Lopez & Mya: Divas of the New Millennium |date=June 1, 2005 |accessdate=July 1, 2012|isbn=9780974977966|page=104|author1=Stacy Deanne |author2=Kelly Kenyatta |author3=Natasha Lowery |author4=Kwynn Sanders |publisher=Amber Books Publishing}}</ref> Prior to the debut of her music, critics wondered why she would take the risk of launching a music career. It was noted that: "If the album was a flop, not only would it embarrass Lopez, but it might even damage her career."<ref name="Latin Sensations">{{cite book|last=Marquez|first=Herón|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q1BW88v0_zMC&pg=PA47 |title=Latin Sensations | page=47 |publisher=Twenty-First Century Books |date=January 1, 2001 |accessdate=July 3, 2012| isbn=9780822549932}}</ref> "[[Waiting for Tonight]]", the third single from ''On the 6'', is widely considered to be Lopez's best song.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stack|first=Tim|title=Jennifer Lopez: 'Waiting for Tonight' was awesome...but it might be time to stop singing|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/11/23/jennifer-lopez-waiting-for-tonight-was-amazing-but-its-time-to-stop-singing/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=March 10, 2012|date=November 23, 2009}}</ref> Lopez's musical success came as a surprise to critics; its launch made the "popular actor even more popular". Both the music industry and the public became intrigued by "this woman who seemed to have so many different talents".<ref name="Latin Sensations"/> By the end of 1999, Lopez successfully converted herself from a film star to a pop star.<ref>{{cite news|title=Puff Daddy out on bail|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/579912.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=July 3, 2012|date=December 28, 1999}}</ref> She joined a select few in achieving this feat, becoming the first since [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]] (1992) and [[Martika]] (1989).<ref name="billboardno1issue" />

===2000–02: Film success, ''J.Lo'' and ''This Is Me... Then'' ===

On February 23, 2000, Lopez, in the accompaniment of then-boyfriend [[Sean Combs]], wore a plunging exotic [[Green Versace dress of Jennifer Lopez|green Versace silk chiffon dress]] on the red carpet of the [[42nd Annual Grammy Awards]]. The dress "had a low-cut neck that extended several inches below her navel, where it was loosely fastened with a sparkly brooch and then opened out again," exposing her midriff and then as cut along the front of the legs like a bath robe.<ref name="PhillipsReay2002">{{cite book|editor1-last=Phillips|editor-first=Kim M.|editor2-last=Reay|editor2-first=Barry|title=Sexualities in history: a reader|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Cz3bPMw_7h4C&pg=PA407|last=Barrera|first=Magdalena|chapter=Hottentot 2000: ''Jennifer Lopez and Her Butt''|accessdate=May 16, 2011|year=2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415929356|page=407}}</ref> The dress generated controversy and media attention, with images of Lopez in the dress being downloaded from the Grammy website over half a million times 24 hours after the event.<ref name="Lee2003">{{cite book|last=Lee|first=Michelle|title=Fashion victim: our love-hate relationship with dressing, shopping, and the cost of style|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E3eBAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=May 16, 2011|date=February 11, 2003|publisher=Broadway Books|isbn=978-0-7679-1048-4|page=122}}</ref> Lopez was surprised by the enormous media coverage, declaring that she had no idea "it was going to become such a big deal".<ref name="OTD">{{cite web|url=http://onthisdayinfashion.com/?p=11475|title=J.Lo Helps Put Donatella—and Herself—on the Fashion Map in That Green Dress|publisher=On This Day in Fashion|date=February 23, 2001|last=Chambers|first=Rachel|accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref> Lopez returned to the big-screen in August, starring in the psychological thriller ''[[The Cell]]'' opposite [[Vincent D'Onofrio]].<ref name="Rovi Cell">{{cite web|first=Mark |last=Deming |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-cell-v195764 |title=The Cell&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}</ref>

During the process of creating her second album, Lopez decided to tweak her image as she began to develop into a [[sex symbol]]. She changed her stage name to J.Lo, a nickname she was given by her fans.<ref name="BookJLo">{{cite book|title=Divas of the new Millennium|year=2005|page=108|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1ZGMcUEvkyEC&pg=PA104&dq=Jennifer+Lopez+if+you+had+my+love#v=onepage&q&f=false|last1=Deanne|first1=Stacy|last2=Kenyatta|first2=Kelly|last3=Lowery|first3=Natasha|last4=Sanders|first4=Kwynn|isbn=9780974977966|accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> She subsequently named the album ''[[J.Lo (album)|J.Lo]]'', which was released on January 23, 2001. The record was a commercial success, debuting at number one on the United States [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=dethroned>{{cite web|title=Lopez Bows At No. 1; O-Town, Dream Debut High5|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/80647/lopez-bows-at-no-1-o-town-dream-debut-high5|work=Billboard |date=January 2001|accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref> This exact week, her romantic comedy film ''[[The Wedding Planner]]'' in which she starred opposite [[Matthew McConaughey]], opened atop the box office. This made her the first woman to have a number one film and album simultaneously.<ref name="timeTyrangiel">{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1093638,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301064251/http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1093638,00.html |archivedate=March 1, 2009 |title=Jennifer Lopez |author=[[Josh Tyrangiel]] |accessdate=January 13, 2007 |work=Time |date=August 13, 2005}}</ref> The album initially spawned the hit singles "[[Love Don't Cost a Thing (song)|Love Don't Cost a Thing]]" and "[[Play (Jennifer Lopez song)|Play]]". April 2001 saw the public launch of [[J.Lo by Jennifer Lopez]], her own clothing and accessory company, which specialized in clothing females of all shapes.<ref name="BookJLo" /> That May, Lopez starred in the romantic drama film ''[[Angel Eyes (film)|Angel Eyes]]'', which performed disappointingly at the box office and generated mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lopez is simply out of sight in 'Angel Eyes'|newspaper=[[The Detroit News]] |date=May 18, 2001}}</ref> In July, an urban oriented "[[Murder Inc Records|Murder]] remix" of the track "[[I'm Real (Jennifer Lopez song)|I'm Real]]" featuring [[Ja Rule]] was released. The remix reached number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=delivery>{{cite web|last=Reid |first=Shaheem |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1448513/ja-rule-helps-j-lo-deliver.jhtml |title=Ja Rule Helps J. Lo Deliver Hot Crossover Joints&nbsp;– Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=[[MTV News]] International, Inc. |date=August 29, 2001 |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> Following the [[September 11 attacks]], Lopez was heavily involved in charitable activities. Joining various other artists, she was featured on charitable singles such as "[[What's Going On (remix album)|What's Going On]]" and "[[El Ultimo Adios (The Last Goodbye)]]", which benefited people affected by the tragedy.<ref name=africa1>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1450237/ll-cool-j-u2s-edge-whats-going-on.jhtml |title=LL Cool J : LL Cool J, U2's Edge, More Join 'What's Going On' Project&nbsp;– Rhapsody Music Downloads |publisher=MTV News |accessdate=March 23, 2012}}</ref><ref name="artistlist">{{cite news |url=http://www.discogs.com/Various-El-Ultimo-Adios-The-Last-Goodbye/release/2075383|title=Complete list of 'El Ultimo Adios' artists |date=May 27, 2011 |publisher=Discogs |accessdate=February 17, 2010 | first=Stephanie | last=J Stone}}</ref>

To enhance Lopez's success in the urban market, promotion of ''J.Lo'' ended and a remix album titled ''[[J to tha L–O! The Remixes]]'' was released on February 5, 2002.<ref name="Billboard Book of Number One Hits">{{cite book |author=Fred Bronson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PgGqNrqfrsoC&pg=PT931&lpg=PT931 |title=The Billboard Book of Number One Hits |edition=5th |publisher=[[Billboard Books]] |year=2003 |isbn=9780823076772 |page=922 |accessdate=April 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lopez|first=Jennifer|title=J to Tha L-O!: The Remixes|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/j-to-tha-l-o!-the-remixes-mw0000658032|work=''[[AllMusic]]''. ''Allrovi Corporation''|accessdate=October 20, 2012}}</ref> Its lead single was "[[Ain't It Funny (Murder Remix)]]", which also featured Ja Rule, which reached number one in the United States. The remix album debuted at the summit of the ''Billboard'' 200, becoming the first to do so.<ref>{{cite web|last=Goodman|first=Abbey|title=Jennifer Lopez Kicks The Boys to the Curb On Next Week's Albums Chart Singer's remix album knocks Alan Jackson, Creed from top of Billboard 200|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1452273/jennifer-lopez-tops-albums-chart.jhtml|publisher=MTV News |accessdate=January 29, 2012|date=February 13, 2002}}</ref> It is the third highest selling remix album in history, with sales of one and a half million in the United States.<ref name="album sales">{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|title=Ask Billboard: Analyzing 'American Idol'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/955571/ask-billboard-analyzing-american-idol|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=January 29, 2012|date=October 1, 2010}}</ref> ''J to tha L–O! The Remixes'' spawned two other singles, "[[I'm Gonna Be Alright]]" and "[[Alive (Jennifer Lopez song)|Alive]]", a ballad co-written by her husband at the time, Cris Judd. April 2002 saw Lopez open her restaurant, ''Madrè's''.<ref name="BookJLo" />

In May 2002, Lopez starred in the thriller film ''[[Enough (film)|Enough]]'' as a woman named Slim who flees her home after being abused by her husband. The film grossed a modest $52 million at the box office,<ref>{{cite web|title=Enough (2002)|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=enough.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=October 20, 2012}}</ref> and garnered lukewarm reviews, despite being dubbed a "kick-butt, female empowerment" movie.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schaefer|first=Stephen|title=Movies: Singer-actress Jennifer Lopez shows her strength in thriller `Enough'|newspaper=[[Boston Herald]] |date=May 19, 2002|location=Boston}}</ref> Filming ''Enough'' required an overworked Lopez to practice [[Krav Maga]], and despite being at the height of her fame at the time, she suffered a [[nervous breakdown]] while on set. Lopez recalled years later feeling "sick and weird", refusing therapeutic help or medication. She confessed, "I was like&nbsp;– I don't want to move, I don't want to talk, I don't want to do anything."<ref>{{cite news|last=Singh|first=Anita|title=Jennifer Lopez: I had a nervous breakdown|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/3152788/Jennifer-Lopez-I-had-a-nervous-breakdown.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=October 20, 2012|date=October 7, 2008}}</ref> In September, Lopez released her first fragrance, [[Glow by JLo]]. It performed strongly despite predictions that it would fail, and became America's top-selling fragrance.<ref name=HS>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qki6zZ4aWd0C&pg=PA6-IA135&dq=Glow+by+JLo&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WAXxT9-fCYjPqgHO_ZDNDQ&ved=0CEUQ6AEwAjgU#v=onepage&q=Glow%20by%20JLo&f=false |title=Beauty Imagined:A History of the Global Beauty Industry|first=Geoffrey|last=Jones |publisher=Oxford University Press|date=February 25, 2010 |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref>

The month of her engagement to actor [[Ben Affleck]] saw the release of her third studio album, ''[[This Is Me... Then]]'', which was dedicated to him. It spawned the internationally successful singles "[[Jenny from the Block]]" and "[[All I Have (song)|All I Have]]". The album itself, which featured multiple love songs,<ref name=dedication>{{cite news|title=J-Lo disc declares her love|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/11/27/1038274342213.html|newspaper=[[The Age]] |accessdate=January 29, 2012|date=November 27, 2002|location=Melbourne, Australia}}</ref> performed strongly, having sold over two and a half million copies in the United States.<ref name="album sales" /> December 2002 saw Lopez star opposite [[Ralph Fiennes]] in the romantic comedy film ''[[Maid in Manhattan]]''. She played Marisa Ventura, a struggling single mother who lives in the Bronx and makes her living cleaning rooms in a super-luxurious Manhattan hotel. Marisa gets mistaken for a socialite by a princely politician, who she falls in love with.<ref>Gary Susman (December 9, 2002). [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,396721_12,00.html "Keeping It Reel"]. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''. Retrieved June 24, 2009. {{wayback|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,396721_12,00.html |date=20090616065531 }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' compared the film's storyline to her song "Jenny from the Block".<ref>A.O. Scott (December 13, 2002). [http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A02E2D7133AF930A25751C1A9649C8B63 "Film Review; Puttin' Down Mop, Puttin' On the Ritz"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. ([[The New York Times Company]]). Retrieved June 24, 2009.</ref>

===2003–09: Career disappointments===

[[File:JenniferLopez.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Lopez in 2004]]

In August 2003, Lopez starred opposite Affleck in the romantic comedy ''[[Gigli]]''. In March 2004, Lopez had a minor role in the film ''[[Jersey Girl (2004 film)|Jersey Girl]]'', alongside Affleck. Her character, Gertrude Steiney, dies during childbirth within the first 15 minutes of the film. From the intense media scrutiny following the couple's break-up, it was noted that "they may need to put Lopez in a coffin on the poster if they want anyone to come".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/4580539/ns/today-entertainment/t/marketing-jersey-girl-post-gigli-world/#.UHM3v03A-So |title=Marketing 'Jersey Girl' in a post-'Gigli' world |publisher=MSNBC |date=March 29, 2004 |accessdate=October 20, 2012}}</ref> In October, Lopez co-starred alongside [[Richard Gere]] in the drama ''[[Shall We Dance? (2004 film)|Shall We Dance?]]'', a re-make of the [[Shall We Dance? (1996 film)|1996 Japanese film of the same title]].

In 2004, during low-key visits to the [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]], which Lopez is an avid support of, she befriended eleven-year-old cancer patient Paige Patterson. Patterson attended the inaugural Noche de Niños gala for the hospital in which Lopez was presented with an award, however the morning after became even more sick and died in November 2004. Lopez has stated that Patterson made her realize why her charity work is important.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news-article/lopez.s-cancer-hero-dies |title=Jennifer Lopez&nbsp;– Lopez's Cancer Hero Dies |publisher=Contactmusic News |date=January 11, 2005 |accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> Lopez dedicated ''[[Rebirth (Jennifer Lopez album)|Rebirth]]'', her fourth studio album, to Patterson.<ref name="Album Credits">{{cite AV media notes |title=Rebirth |others=Jennifer Lopez |year=2005 |type=Booklet |publisher=[[Epic Records]]}}</ref> According to Lopez, ''Rebirth'' "came about because I was on such a roller-coaster ride, that was my career from my first album to my last album, and I did a bunch of movie projects in between. I finally took some time just for myself, and [when] I came back, this was the first project I did. I felt like it was a new beginning for me, like I was, in a way, reborn. I was where I was when I made my first album".<ref name=virgin>{{cite web|last=Goodman |first=Abbey |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1497737/jennifer-lopez-on-rebirth-new-beginning.jhtml |title=Jennifer Lopez Calls Rebirth 'A New Beginning'&nbsp;– Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV News |date=March 3, 2005 |accessdate=April 29, 2012}}</ref> Tracy Hopkins of NBC's [[NBC|Today Music]] noted that after "fawning" over Affleck on ''This Is Me... Then''", Lopez "wisely keeps her love life out of the spotlight" on ''Rebirth'' and only references her relationship with Anthony on a few tracks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://msnbc.msn.com/id/7047411/site/todayshow/ns/today-entertainment/t/rebirth-its-best-when-j-lo-keeps-it-dance-floor/ |title='Rebirth' at its best on dance floor |publisher=MSNBC |date=February 3, 2005 |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref>

In May, Lopez starred alongside [[Jane Fonda]] in the romantic comedy ''[[Monster-in-Law]]''. She received $15&nbsp;million for her role as Charlie, an artist who is pitted against her fiance's mother when she does not accept her as being the right woman for her son.<ref name=fonda>{{cite news|last=Lumenick|first=Lou|title=So Fonda The Fight|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|publisher=[[News Corporation]]|date=March 13, 2005|page=48}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lowe|first=Kinsey R.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/may/16/entertainment/et-boxoffice16|title='Monster-in-Law' gets a cheery reception; The comedy with Jane Fonda and Jennifer Lopez debuts at No.1 on another weekend off the pace set in 2004.|accessdate=January 30, 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 16, 2005|location=Los Angeles, California}}</ref> In August, Lopez starred alongside [[Robert Redford]] and [[Morgan Freeman]] in ''[[An Unfinished Life]]'', a drama film based on the novel of the same name.

[[File:Jennifer Lopez 2008.jpg|thumb|upright|Lopez in 2008]]

''[[Bordertown (2006 film)|Bordertown]]'', a film based on the [[Female homicides in Ciudad Juárez]], made its premiere at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] on May 18, 2006. Lopez, who also acts as the film's producer, stars as Lauren Adrian, an American news reporter for the Chicago Sentinel who wants to be assigned to the Iraq front-lines to cover the war.<ref>{{cite news|last=Summers|first=Chris|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/5268558.stm|title=Hollywood tackles Mexican mystery|date=September 10, 2006|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=July 24, 2012}}</ref> ''[[DanceLife]]'', a reality series following the lives of seven dancers trying to break into the world of professional dance, aired on MTV from January 15 to March 5, 2007. Lopez produced, created and was featured in the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/shows/dancelife/series.jhtml |title=Dancelife &#124; Full Episodes, Photos, Episode Synopsis and Recaps |publisher=MTV News |accessdate=August 8, 2012}}</ref> According to the album's co-producer Estéfano, Lopez's fifth studio album ''[[Como Ama una Mujer]]'' would "prove critics wrong" with its "big songs that require a voice"; referring to the criticism of Lopez having a "limited" vocal tone.<ref name="Contactmusic Rebirth">{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/pages/jenniferlopezx18x03x05|title=Jennifer Lopez&nbsp;– Rebirth&nbsp;– Album Review |publisher=Contactmusic News |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name="Contactmusic Spanish">{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news-article/j.lo-to-prove-critics-wrong-with-spanish-album_30_01_2006 |title=Jennifer Lopez&nbsp;– J.Lo To Prove Critics Wrong With Spanish Album |publisher=Contactmusic News |date=January 30, 2006 |accessdate=June 3, 2012}}</ref> The album received the highest first-week sales in the United States for a Spanish album and the highest digital sales.<ref name="Como Ama Una Mujer Breaks Records">{{cite news |title=Jennifer Lopez's First Spanish-Language Album is an Instant No. 1 on the Billboard Latin Chart |url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/spanish/jennifer/prweb517033.htm |publisher=PRWeb |accessdate=January 29, 2012|location=New York|date=April 6, 2007}}</ref>

In September 2007, Lopez starred in the [[biographical film]] ''[[El Cantante]]'', which is based on the life of the late [[salsa music|salsa]] singer [[Héctor Lavoe]]. In the film, Lavoe is portrayed by then-husband [[Marc Anthony]] while Lopez plays Lavoe's wife Puchi.<ref name="CantanteNYReview">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/03/movies/03cant.html?_r=0 |title=When the Salsa Throbs, a Singer's Soul Is Revealed |newspaper=The New York Times |last=Scott|first=A. O.|date=August 3, 2007 |accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref> In an interview with [[Latina magazine]], Lopez revealed that she felt her performance in the film ''El Cantante'', should have earned her an Oscar.<ref name="CantanteOscar">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/jennifer-lopez-deserved-oscar-nomination-role-el-cantante-article-1.198079 |title=Jennifer Lopez: I deserved an Oscar nomination for my role in 'El Cantante' |newspaper=New York Daily News |last=Eisinger|first=Amy|date=January 6, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref> "I feel like I had that [Oscar worthy role] in 'El Cantante,' but I don't think the academy members saw it".<ref name="CantanteOscar"/> Lopez and Anthony also launched their [[Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony en Concierto|co-headlining North American concert tour]] on September 28. The tour grossed an estimated $10 million, with one dollar from each ticket sold being donated to Run for Something Better—a charitable organization supporting physical fitness programs for children.<ref>{{cite news|author=Cobo, Leila|date=June 7, 2008|title=Together Again|work=Billboard|volume=120|issue=23 |issn=0006-2510|accessdate=May 28, 2012|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_hIEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=10}}</ref><ref name="ld1">{{cite web|url=http://www.soundspike.com/story2/12624/jennifer-lopez-to-drop-brave-new-album/|title=Jennifer Lopez to drop 'Brave' new album|last=Kilgore|first=Kym|date=August 13, 2007|accessdate=September 4, 2010|work=LiveDaily|archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1338238555ICJBKARMZN |archivedate=May 28, 2012}}</ref>

Lopez's sixth studio album ''[[Brave (Jennifer Lopez album)|Brave]]'', released in October, was her lowest-charting album worldwide.<ref name="lovereview"/> The album produced two singles, "[[Do It Well]]" and "[[Hold It Don't Drop It]]". The first peaked at number 31 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, while the latter failed to make any significant impact on the charts. A five-part [[miniseries]], ''[[Jennifer Lopez Presents: Como Ama una Mujer]]'', based on the lyrics of ''Como Ama una Mujer'' aired on [[Univision]] from October 30 to November 27, 2007. In late 2009, Lopez released two songs for her seventh studio album, ''[[Love? (album)|Love?]]'' ("[[Louboutins (song)|Louboutins]]" and "Fresh Out of the Oven"); however, the songs failed to make an appearance on the ''Billboard'' charts which led to her departure from [[Epic Records]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/louboutins-fresh-oven-flop-epic-records-jennifer-lopez-boot-source-article-1.194874 |title=After 'Louboutins', 'Fresh Out of the Oven' flop, Epic Records gives Jennifer Lopez the boot: source |newspaper=New York Daily News |author=Gatecrasher|date=February 23, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref>

===2010–12: Career rejuvenation and ''American Idol''===
Lopez parted ways with Epic Records in February 2010, citing that she had fulfilled her contractual obligations and now wished to release her seventh studio album ''[[Love?]]'' under a new label.<ref name="Billboard Lopez Leaves Sony">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/959279/updated-jennifer-lopez-confirms-split-with-epic-records |title=Updated: Jennifer Lopez Confirms Split With Epic Records |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |author1=Concepcion, Mariel |author2=Ben-Yehuda, Ayala |author3=Caulfield, Kieth |date=February 23, 2010 |accessdate=March 16, 2010}}</ref> Her departure from the label temporarily halted production on the album, which commenced in 2009. Upon signing a new contract with [[Island Records]], recording resumed on the album.<ref>{{cite news |author=Sarah |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/record-producer-spills-justin-bieber-katy-perry-and-j-los-studio-secrets-2010167 |title=Record Producer Spills Justin Bieber, Katy Perry and J.Lo's Studio Secrets |work=[[Us Weekly]] |date=June 16, 2010 |accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref> The ''[[New York Daily News]]'' revealed that Lopez would be taking some of the records recorded under Sony Music Entertainment to her new label so that they could be included on the album.<ref>{{cite news|author=Gatecrasher |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-02-24/gossip/27057095_1_el-cantante-sony-music-second-source |title=After 'Louboutins', 'Fresh Out of the Oven' flop, Epic Records gives Jennifer Lopez the boot |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=February 24, 2010 |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> In April, Lopez starred in the romantic comedy ''[[The Back-up Plan]]'', her first theatrical role in three years.<ref name="Rovi Back Up Plan">{{cite web|first=Jason |last=Buchanan |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-back-up-plan-v490905 |title=The Back-up Plan&nbsp;– Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}</ref> In June, following the departure of [[Ellen DeGeneres]] from ''[[American Idol]]'', it was reported that Lopez was in talks to join season ten's judging panel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebritynews/news/source-jennifer-lopez-to-be-an-american-idol-judge-2010307 |title=Source: Jennifer Lopez to Be an American Idol Judge&nbsp;– Celebrity News |work=Us Weekly |accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2010/07/29/2010-07-29_ellen_degeneres_leaving_american_idol.html | newspaper=New York Daily News |title=Ellen DeGeneres leaves 'American Idol'; Jennifer Lopez reportedly close to replacing her | first=Bill | last=Hutchinson | date=July 30, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/07/american-idols-backup-plan-with-jennifer-lopez-not-ready-for-delivery.html | work=Los Angeles Times | title=Show Tracker | date=July 30, 2010}}</ref> During this same time, Lopez and Anthony were being considered for a role on ''[[The X Factor (U.S.)|The X Factor]]'' for their appeal to Latin and International markets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a219700/lopez-anthony-linked-to-us-x-factor.html |title=US TV&nbsp;– News&nbsp;– Lopez, Anthony linked to US 'X Factor' |publisher=[[Digital Spy]] |date=May 13, 2010 |accessdate=September 18, 2010}}</ref> It was officially announced in September that Lopez would be joining the [[American Idol (season 10)|tenth season]] of ''American Idol''. MTV stated that the deal was "mutually beneficial to all those involved", while [[CNN]] reported that Lopez was viewing it as a decision to revive her career, while ''American Idol'' producers believed that Lopez and [[Steven Tyler]]'s appointments would strengthen viewing figures.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/09/22/jennifer.lopez.american.idol/ |publisher=CNN | title=Jennifer Lopez: A reality TV revival? | date=September 23, 2010}}</ref> In October, Lopez released her fourteenth fragrance, Love and Glamour. The perfume was inspired by Lopez's forthcoming "return to the spotlight".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.instyle.com/2010/06/07/jennifer-lopez-launches-love-and-glamour |title=Jennifer Lopez Launches Love and Glamour |work=[[InStyle]] |date=June 7, 2010 |accessdate=August 8, 2012}}</ref>

