'''Alicia Patterson''' (October 15, 1906 – July 2, 1963) was the founder and editor of ''[[Newsday]]'', which became a respected and [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning newspaper. With [[Neysa McMein]], she created the ''Deathless Deer'' comic strip in 1943.

==Early life==
Alicia was the middle daughter of Alice (née Higinbotham) and [[Joseph Medill Patterson]],{{r|Smith}} the founder of the ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'',{{r|Schultz}} and the great-granddaughter of [[Joseph Medill]],{{r|Smith}} owner of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''.{{r|Sicherman}}{{efn|Her paternal aunt, Eleanor Medill Patterson was the publisher of the ''[[Washington Times-Herald]]''.{{r|Sicherman}}}} Her mother's father was Harlow Higinbotham, partner of [[Marshall Field's|Marshall Field's Department Store]] in Chicago.{{r|Sicherman}}{{r|Miller}} Patterson's sisters were [[Cissy Patterson|Elinor]] (1906–1984) and Josephine (1913–1963).{{r|Smith}}

The family lived on a farm in [[Libertyville, Illinois]] in her earliest years, during a period when her father eschewed capitalism. He returned to the publishing world in 1910, as editor of the ''Chicago Tribune''.{{r|Sicherman}} He sent Patterson to Germany to live with a family and learn German when she was four years old.{{r|Sicherman}} During her childhood, Patterson was raised by her father as if she were his son. He taught her daring sports, like high diving and jumping while horseback riding, to test her courage.{{r|Sicherman}}

Patterson attended the [[Francis W. Parker School (Chicago)|Francis Parker School]] and [[University School for Girls]] in Chicago. She was then sent to [[finishing school]]s in Maryland and [[Lausanne]], Switzerland, from which she was expelled for violating the rules.{{r|Sicherman}} She attended the [[Foxcroft School]] in Virginia, where she finished second in her class, and was then sent to a school in Rome where she was expelled for behavior issues.{{r|Sicherman}}

At age 19 years, she had her [[Debutante|coming-out party]] in Chicago, after having spent a year in Europe with her mother and sister.{{r|Sicherman}}

Her half-brother, [[James Joseph Patterson|James J. Patterson]] (1922–1992), was the son of Joseph Patterson and Mary King (1885–1975),{{r|Smith}} who married in 1938, the same year James' and Alice's divorce was finalized.{{r|Miller p. 371}}

