| title = Topping The Charts Year By Year
| journal = Billboard
| volume = 110
| issue = 48
| page = LMQ3
| url = https://books.google.com/?id=MAoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA38&dq=rudy+la+scala&cd=1#v=onepage&q=rudy%20la%20scala
| accessdate =March 3, 2010| author1 =
Nielsen Business Media| first1 =
Inc}}</ref><ref name="numberonesingles">{{cite news |title=Remembering Selena's Trailblazing Music |author=Rivas, Jorge |url=http://colorlines.com/archives/2011/03/16th_anniversary_of_selenas_death.html |newspaper=Colorlines |date=March 31, 2011 |accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref> The album's commercial success led to a Grammy nomination for Best Mexican/American Album at the [[37th Grammy Awards]] in 1995.<ref name="nominations">{{cite news |title=Loving Selena, fans loved themselves |first=Alisa|last=Valdes |url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/21566588.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+07%2C+1995&author=Alisa+Valdes%2C+Globe+Staff&pub=Boston+Globe+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Loving+Selena%2C+fans+loved+themselves&pqatl=google |newspaper=[[Boston Globe]] |date=April 7, 1995 |accessdate=August 14, 2011|subscription=yes}}</ref> It won Record of the Year at the [[1995 Tejano Music Awards]]<ref name="TMAs"/> and Regional/Mexican Album of the Year at the [[Premio Lo Nuestro 1995|1995 Lo Nuestro Awards]].{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=152}} Selena was named "one of Latin music's most successful touring acts" during her ''Amor Prohibido'' tour.<ref name=richard>{{cite news|last1=Harrington|first1=Richard|title=Slain Tejano Singer's Album Tops Pop Chart|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/review97/selenaalbum.htm|accessdate=February 28, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=July 26, 1995}}</ref> After ''Amor Prohibido''{{'}}s release, Selena was considered "bigger than Tejano itself", and broke barriers in the Latin music world.<ref name=Newsday>{{cite news|last=Schone|first=Mark|title=A Postmortem Star In death, Selena is a crossover success|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/20467875.html?dids=20467875:20467875&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+20%2C+1995&author=By+Mark+Schone.+Mark+Schone+is+a+free-lance+writer.&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=A+Postmortem+Star+In+death%2C+Selena+is+a+crossover+success&pqatl=google|accessdate=November 4, 2011|newspaper=Newsday|date=April 20, 1995}}</ref> She was called the "Queen of Tejano music" by many media outlets.{{efn|Outlets describing Selena as "Queen of Tejano music" include: ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cortina|first=Betty|title=A Sad Note|journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=March 26, 1999|issue=478|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,274898,00.html|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> ''Billboard'' magazine,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lannert|first=John|title=Tejano Music Awards: Bigger, But Not Necessarily Better|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=April 6, 1996|volume=108|issue=14|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Tw0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA37&lpg=PA37&dq=Selena+Queen+of+Tejano+Music#v=onepage&q=Selena%20Queen%20of%20Tejano%20Music&f=false|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Los Angeles (magazine)|Los Angeles Magazine]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last=Katz|first=Jesse|title=The Curse of Zapata|journal=[[Los Angeles (magazine)|Los Angeles Magazine]] |date=December 2002 |volume=47 |issue=12 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=7V0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA104&lpg=PA104&dq=Selena+Queen+of+Tejano+Music#v=onepage&q=Selena%20Queen%20of%20Tejano%20Music&f=false|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' magazine,<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Year In Review|journal=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=September 1998|volume=6|issue=7|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lywEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA167&lpg=PA167&dq=Selena+Queen+of+Tejano+Music#v=onepage&q=Selena%20Queen%20of%20Tejano%20Music&f=false|accessdate=September 11, 2012|author1=Group|first1=Vibe Media}}</ref> ''[[The Huffington Post]]'',<ref name=huff>{{cite news|last1=Hernandez|first1=Lee|title=Selena Quintanilla: Remembering The Queen Of Tejano Music On Her Birthday|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/15/selena-quintanilla-birthday-tejano_n_1425195.html|accessdate=January 30, 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=April 15, 2012}}</ref> and ''The New York Times''.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|last1=Verhovek|first1=Sam|title=Grammy-Winning Singer Selena Killed in Shooting at Texas Motel|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/01/obituaries/grammy-winning-singer-selena-killed-in-shooting-at-texas-motel.html|accessdate=January 30, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>}} Sales of the album and its titular single represented Tejano music's first commercial success in Puerto Rico.<ref name=Newsday/> Selena recorded a duet titled "[[Donde Quiera Que Estés]]" with the [[Barrio Boyzz]], which was released on their album of the same name in 1994. The song reached number one on the Top Latin Songs chart,<ref name="Allmusic">{{cite web |url=http://www.allrovi.com/name/The-Barrio-Boyzz-p448538?r=allmovie |title=Chart history > Selena > Donde Quiera Que Estes|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=July 13, 2011}}</ref> which enabled Selena to tour in New York City, Argentina, Puerto Rico, the Dominican Republic, and Central America, where she was not well known.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=123}}{{sfn|Jones|2013|p=14}} In late 1994, EMI chairman [[Charles Koppelman]] decided Selena had achieved her goals in the Spanish-speaking market. He wanted to promote her as an English-language, American, solo pop artist. Selena continued touring while EMI began preparing the crossover album, engaging Grammy Award-winning composers.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=115}} By the time Selena performed to a record-breaking, sold out concert at the [[Houston Astrodome]] in February 1995, work had already begun on her crossover album.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=115}} In 1995, she made a [[cameo appearance]] in ''[[Don Juan DeMarco]]'', which starred [[Marlon Brando]], [[Johnny Depp]], and [[Faye Dunaway]].<ref name="The Atlanta Journal">{{cite news|title=Selena: Singer was on the verge of mainstream stardom|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADA1B37718A8B2&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=October 11, 2011|newspaper=The Atlanta Journal|date=April 5, 1995|subscription=yes}}</ref>

== Murder ==
{{main|Murder of Selena|Trial of Yolanda Saldívar}}
The Quintanilla family appointed Saldívar manager of Selena's boutiques in early 1994.<ref name=orlando/> Eight months later, Selena signed Saldívar as her [[registered agent]] in San Antonio, Texas. After the agreement, Saldívar moved from San Antonio to Corpus Christi to be closer to Selena.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=146}} In December 1994, the boutiques began to suffer after the number of staff for both stores had decreased.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=182}} According to staff members, Saldívar often dismissed employees she personally disliked.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=170}} Staff at the stores regularly complained about Saldívar's behavior to Selena, who dismissed the claims, believing Saldívar would not negatively impose erratic decisions on Selena's fashion venture.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=170}} According to Quintanilla, Jr., the staff later turned their attention to him and began informing him about Saldívar's behavior. Quintanilla, Jr. took the claims seriously; he told Selena to "be careful" and said Saldívar may not be a good influence.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=170}} Selena dismissed her father's inquiries because he had often distrusted people in the past.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=170}} By January 1995, Selena's cousin, her fashion designer Martin Gomez, and clients expressed their concerns over Saldívar's behavior and management skills.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=170}}{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=171}} During an interview with Saldívar in 1995, reporters from ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' said her devotion to Selena bordered on obsession.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=146}}

According to Quintanilla, Jr., in January 1995 he began receiving telephone calls from fans who said they had paid for membership in the Selena fan club and had received nothing in return for it, and he began an investigation.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=183}} Quintanilla, Jr. discovered that Saldívar had embezzled more than $60,000 in forged checks from both the fan club and the boutiques.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=183}} Quintanilla, Jr. held a meeting with Selena and Suzette on the night of March 9 at [[Q-Productions]] to confront Saldívar. Quintanilla, Jr. presented Saldívar with the inconsistencies concerning the disappearing funds. Quintanilla, Jr. told her that if she did not provide evidence that disproved his accusations, he would involve the local police. Quintanilla, Jr. banned Saldívar from having any contact with Selena.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=183}} However, Selena did not want to dissolve their friendship; she thought Saldívar was essential to the success of the clothing line in Mexico. Selena also wanted to keep her close because she had bank records, statements, and financial records necessary for tax preparation.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=183}}

On the morning of March 31, 1995, Selena met with Saldívar at her [[Days Inn]] motel room in Corpus Christi.<ref name=NewYorkTimes/> At the motel, Selena demanded the financial papers; Saldívar delayed the handover by saying she had been raped in Mexico.<ref name="queen"/> Selena then drove Saldívar to Doctors Regional Hospital, where doctors found no evidence of rape.<ref name="Rape">{{cite news|title=October 12, 1995 testimony of Carla Anthony |url=http://chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/transcripts/95/10/12/anthony.html |accessdate=September 27, 2015 |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=October 12, 1995 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406191637/http://chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/transcripts/95/10/12/anthony.html |archivedate=April 6, 2007 }}</ref> At 11:48 a.m. (CST), Saldívar drew a gun from her purse<ref>{{cite web|last=Hewitt |first=Bill |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20105524,00.html |title=Before Her Time&nbsp;– Death, Murder, Selena |work=People |date=April 17, 1995 |accessdate=June 8, 2010}}</ref> and pointed it at Selena.<ref name="FCS">{{Cite episode |series=[[Famous Crime Scene]] |episodelink= |title=Selena |serieslink= |credits= |network=[[VH1]] |station= |airdate=March 12, 2010 |season=1 |number=105 |minutes=30 }}</ref> As Selena attempted to flee, Saldívar shot her once on the right lower shoulder, severing an artery and causing a massive loss of blood.<ref name="FCS"/> Critically wounded, Selena ran towards the lobby, leaving a {{convert|392|ft|m|adj=on}}-long trail of blood.<ref name="FCS"/> She collapsed on the floor as the clerk called the emergency services, with Saldívar still chasing after her and calling her a "bitch".<ref name="Bitch">{{cite news|title=October 12, 1995, the testimony of Norma Martinez |url=http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/transcripts/95/10/12/martinez.html |accessdate=September 27, 2015 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=October 12, 1995 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715183634/http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/transcripts/95/10/12/martinez.html |archivedate=July 15, 2007 }}</ref> Before collapsing, Selena named Saldívar as her assailant and gave the number of the room where she had been shot.<ref name="Assailant">{{cite news|title=Friday, October 13, testimony of Shawna Vela |url=http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/transcripts/95/10/13/vela.html |accessdate=September 27, 2015 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=October 13, 1995 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070710205035/http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/transcripts/95/10/13/vela.html |archivedate=July 10, 2007 }}</ref> Meanwhile, Saldívar got into her pickup truck and tried to leave the motel. However, she was spotted by a responding police cruiser.<ref name="FCS"/> Saldívar surrendered after a nearly nine-and-a-half-hour standoff with police and the FBI.<ref name=NewYorkTimes/> By that time, hundreds of fans had gathered at the scene; many wept as police took Saldívar away.<ref name=NewYorkTimes/><ref name="FCS"/> After 50 minutes of surgery, the doctors realized that the damage to Selena's pierced artery was irreparable. Selena Quintanilla-Pérez was pronounced dead from [[Bleeding|blood loss]] and [[cardiac arrest]] at 1:05 p.m. (CST).<ref name="FCS"/><ref name="Death">{{cite news|last1=Villafranca |first1=Armando |title=Singer Selena shot to death |url=http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/95/04/01/killed.html |accessdate=September 27, 2015 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=April 1, 1995 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621144534/http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/95/04/01/killed.html |archivedate=June 21, 2007 }}</ref>

=== Impact ===
Selena's murder had a widespread impact. Reactions to her death were compared to those following the deaths of musicians [[John Lennon]], [[Elvis Presley]], and [[President of the United States|U.S. president]] [[John F. Kennedy]].{{sfn|Stacy|2002|p=746}}{{sfn|Jasinski|2012|p=254}} Major television networks interrupted their regular programming to break the news; [[Tom Brokaw]] referred to Selena as "The Mexican [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Gregory|title='Selena': A Symbol of Today's Cultural Ties|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997-04-07/entertainment/ca-46202_1_mexican-american-identity|accessdate=September 27, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=April 7, 1997}}</ref> Her death was front page news in ''[[The New York Times]]'' for two days.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=174}} Numerous vigils and memorials were held in her honor, and radio stations in Texas played her music non-stop.<ref name="worstday">{{cite news|title=Selena's death leaves Tejano music world shocked, mournful |url=http://www.caller.com/entertainment/selena/selenas-death-leaves-tejano-music-world-shocked-mournful-ep-1035569575.html |accessdate=September 19, 2015 |work=Corpus Christi Caller Times |date=April 1, 1995}}</ref> Her funeral drew 60,000 mourners, many of whom traveled from outside the United States.<ref name="worstday"/> The news struck the [[Hispanic]] community extremely hard; many fans traveled thousands of miles to see Selena's house and boutiques, and the crime scene.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=199}}<ref name="traffic">{{cite news |title=For Barrio, Selena's Death Strikes a Poignant Chord Tragedy: Fans descend on superstar's home in Texas community. Idolized singer didn't forget her roots |first=Jesse|last=Katz |url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/22766431.html?dids=22766431:22766431&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+02%2C+1995&author=JESSE+KATZ&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=For+Barrio%2C+Selena%27s+Death+Strikes+a+Poignant+Chord+Tragedy%3A+Fans+descend+on+superstar%27s+home+in+Texas+community.+Idolized+singer+didn%27t+forget+her+roots.&pqatl=google |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=April 2, 1995 |accessdate=September 15, 2011}}</ref> By mid-afternoon, police were asked to form a [[detour]] because a line of cars began backing up traffic from the Quintanillas' houses.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=200}} Among the celebrities who were reported to have contacted the Quintanilla family to express their condolences were Gloria Estefan, [[Celia Cruz]], [[Julio Iglesias]], and Madonna.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=165}} Other celebrities—including [[Stefanie Ridel]], Jaime DeAnda (of [[Tejano music#Tejano artists and bands|Los Chamacos]]), and [[Shelly Lares]]—appeared on radio stations to express their thoughts about Selena's death.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=201}} An issue of ''People'' magazine was released several days after her murder. Its publishers believed interest would soon wane; they released a commemorative issue within a week when it became apparent it was growing. The issue sold nearly a million copies,<ref name="Latin pride">{{cite journal |last1=Lannert |first1=John |year=1995 |title=Latin pride |journal=Billboard |volume=107 |issue=23 |page=112 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=0QsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA62&dq=Selena+Dreaming+of+You+sold+more#v=onepage&q=Selena%20Dreaming%20of%20You%20sold%20more&f=false|accessdate=September 27, 2015 }}</ref> selling the entire first and second print runs within two weeks. It became a collector's item, a first in the history of ''People''.<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/> Betty Cortina, editor of ''People'', told ''Biography'' they never had an issue that was completely sold out; "it was unheard of".<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/> In the following months, the company released ''[[People en Español]]'' aimed at the Hispanic market, due to the success of the Selena issue.<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/> This was followed by ''[[Newsweek|Newsweek en Espanol]]'' and ''[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]'' magazine.<ref name=muniz>{{cite web|last1=Muniz|first1=Janet|title=Bidi Bidi Bom Bom: The Audiotopias of Selena Across the Americas|url=http://scholarship.claremont.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1045&context=lux|website=''[[Claremont Graduate University|Claremont.edu]]''|accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref>

A few days later, [[Howard Stern]] mocked Selena's murder and burial, poked fun at her mourners, and criticized her music. Stern said, "This music does absolutely nothing for me. [[Alvin and the Chipmunks]] have more soul&nbsp;...&nbsp;Spanish people have the worst taste in music. They have no depth." Stern's comments outraged and infuriated the Hispanic community in Texas.{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|pp=24–27}} Stern played Selena's songs with gunshots in the background on his show.{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|p=24}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Keveney|first1=Bill|title=Howard Stern Returns, by Syndication to Hartford Station he left in 1980|url=http://plp.ccc.commnet.edu:6012/hartfordcourant/docview/255830990/62D930A408AF42BFPQ/24?accountid=39924|accessdate=February 28, 2015|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=March 26, 1996}}</ref> After a [[disorderly conduct]] arrest warrant was issued in his name, Stern made an on-air statement, in Spanish, saying his comments were not made to cause "more anguish to her family, friends and those who loved her".<ref name=NYDailyNews1995>{{cite web|title=A real shocker from Stern: Apology for Selena comments|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/real-shocker-stern-apology-selena-comments-article-1.689006|work=Daily News|location=New York|accessdate=November 23, 2013|date=April 7, 1995}}</ref><ref name=ABCNews2012>{{cite web|last=Marikar|first=Sheila|title=Howard Stern's Five Most Outrageous Offenses|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/howard-sterns-outrageous-offenses/story?id=16327309|work= Good Morning America|publisher=ABC|accessdate=November 23, 2013|date=May 14, 2012}}</ref> Stern was not formally charged; the [[League of United Latin American Citizens]] boycotted Stern's show, finding his apology unacceptable.<ref name="stern">{{cite news |title=Hispanics call Stern's apology for Selena remarks unacceptable |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF8FF3E2963B7B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |newspaper=Fort Worth Star-Telegram |date=April 7, 1995 |accessdate=September 20, 2011|subscription=yes}}</ref> Texas retailers removed any products that were related to Stern, while [[Sears]] and [[McDonald's]] sent a letter stating their disapproval of Stern's comments to the media, because some fans believed the companies sponsored Stern's show.{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|pp=26–27}} Within a week, on [[NBC]]'s ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'', Stern and [[Robin Quivers]] (his co-host) were asked whether Stern's remarks about Selena were acceptable. Quivers decided not to talk about the situation to avoid arguing with Stern. When [[Linda Ronstadt]]—a pop singer of Mexican-American heritage—appeared on the show, she and Quivers argued when Ronstadt defended Selena.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=227}}

On April 12, 1995, two weeks after Selena's death, [[George W. Bush]], governor of Texas at the time, declared her birthday, April 16, [[Selena Day]] in the state.<ref name="biotexas"/><ref name=WIRE>{{cite news|last=Reports|first=Wire|title=Sunday's Selena Day|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAFE75514FF3445&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=October 6, 2011|newspaper=San Antonio Express-News|date=April 14, 1995|subscription=yes}}</ref> He said Selena represented "the essence of south Texas culture." who never forgot where she came from.<ref name=bushcomments>{{cite web|title=Texas Declares `Selena Day'|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Texas-Declares-Selena-Day-3037474.php|website=[[Houston Chronicle]]|accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref> Some European Americans in Texas wrote to the editor of the ''[[Brazosport Facts]]'' during April and May, asking what the big deal was; some were offended that Selena Day fell on [[Easter Sunday]]. Others said, "Easter is ''more'' important than Selena Day", and that they believed people should let Selena rest in peace and continue with their lives.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=225}} Mexican Americans in Texas wrote vociferously to the newspaper. Some said others were too critical of Selena Day, and should not have responded so rudely.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=226}} In October 1995, a Houston jury convicted Saldívar of [[first-degree murder]] and sentenced her to life in prison with the possibility of parole in 2025.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=230}} In 2002, under a judge's order, the gun used to kill Selena was destroyed and the pieces were thrown into [[Corpus Christi Bay]].<ref name="Gun">{{cite news|title=Southwest: Texas: Gun That Killed Singer Is To Be Destroyed|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/08/us/national-briefing-southwest-texas-gun-that-killed-singer-is-to-be-destroyed.html|accessdate=September 27, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=June 8, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-06-11/news/0206110189_1_tejano-singing-star-selena-abraham-quintanilla-corpus-christi-bay |title=Gun used in slaying of Selena destroyed | work=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=October 26, 2011 |date=June 11, 2002 |first=Items |last=Compiled|subscription=yes}}</ref> Fans and historians disapproved of the decision to destroy the gun, saying the event was historical and the gun should have been in a museum.<ref name="biotexas"/>

== Artistry ==
Selena's [[vocal range]] was [[soprano]].<ref name=mendoza/> In an April 1995 interview with ''Billboard'' magazine, Behar said he saw Selena as a "cross between [[Janet Jackson]] and [[Whitney Houston]] in style, feel, and vocal range".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Burr|first1=Ramiro|title=EMI Set Honors Selena's Memory|journal=Billboard|date=April 15, 1995|volume=107|issue=15|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7wsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA72&dq=Selena+Quintanilla+vocal+range#v=onepage&q=Selena%20Quintanilla%20vocal%20range&f=false|accessdate=February 2, 2015}}</ref> Although Selena did not write most of her songs, she incorporated [[contemporary R&B|R&B]],{{sfn|Ilan|2014|p=668}} [[Latin pop]], [[synthpop|technopop]],{{sfn|Stacy|2002|p=745}} [[country western music|country and western]], and [[disco]] into her Tejano music repertoire.{{sfn|Moreno|2010|p=282}} Mario Tarradell of ''The Dallas Morning News'' said that during her music career, Selena "merges Tejano's infectious cumbia rhythm with street-savvy R&B, old-school soul, dancehall reggae, sizzling salsa, and trippy, loopy funk".{{sfn|Gutiérrez|2003|p=122}} Selena's recordings expressed "love and pain, as well as strength and passion", according to Charles Tatum.{{sfn|Tatum|2013|p=1032}} She also recorded independently driven, female-empowerment-themed compositions; "Si La Quieres", "¿Qué Creías?", "Ya Ves" and "Ya No", which centered around inappropriate relationships and recovery from domestic violence.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=121}} Peter Watrous of ''The New York Times'' said Selena's voice "sometimes quivered", and that she "roughed it up a bit". He continued, "[a]t its best, it had a coolness, a type of unadorned passion".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Watrous|first1=Peter|title=Recordings View;; Inklings of What Might Have Been|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/30/arts/recordings-view-inklings-of-what-might-have-been.html|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 30, 1995}}</ref> [[Ilan Stavans]] called her music "cursi-melodramatic, cheesy, overemotional, not too far from [[Juan Gabriel]] and a relative of Iglesias".<ref name=dreamingrep>{{cite news|last1=Stavans |first1=Ilan |title=Dreaming of You |url=http://plp.ccc.commnet.edu:6135/ehost/detail/detail?sid=7ed433f3-954f-4d83-838c-c2ca0c99b232%40sessionmgr4004&vid=0&hid=4104&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ%3d%3d#db=buh&AN=9511303094 |accessdate=March 26, 2015 |work=New Republic |date=November 20, 1995 |subscription=yes }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> [[Richard Corliss]] of ''Time'' magazine said her songs "are perky, cheerful rather than soulful", and that earlier recordings, "with their tinny, Tijuana Brass charts, and keyboards that evoke calliopes, are ideal for the fairground or merry-go-round". Corliss calls Selena's singing an "expert mimicry of everything from Édith Piaf's melodramatic contralto to the coloratura riffs of Mariah Carey. But the sounds are still lightly Hispanic."<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Corliss|first1=Richard|title=Viva Selena|journal=Time|date=June 24, 2001|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,137442,00.html|accessdate=March 26, 2015}}</ref>

{{Listen|filename=Selena-DreamingOfYou-wiki.ogg|title="Dreaming of You" (1995)|description="Dreaming of You", an English-language recording, became one of four English cuts Selena recorded for her crossover from Spanish into English pop music.|format=[[Ogg]]}}

''Newsweek'' magazine called Selena's English-language recordings "a blend of urban pop and Latin warmth".<ref name=newsweek>{{cite web|title=Selena's Posthumous Triumph|url=http://www.newsweek.com/selenas-posthumous-triumph-184534|website=[[Newsweek]]|accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref> According to ''[[Texas Monthly]]'',  Selena's brother modernized her music into a more "funk and hip hop" sound.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Topics > Selena|journal=[[Texas Monthly]]|url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/topics/selena|accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref> Selena's use of emotive range during her musical career has been praised by critics as being her trademark.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Latin Style|year=2002|issue=45|quote=The song "My Love," was written by Selena and samples from contemporary pop influences. Other songs like "Sukiyaki" (a cover of Kyu Sakamoto's 1963 hit), "Amame, Quiéreme" (her first duet with Pete Astudillo), and the cumbia “Besitos”, played a pivotal role on how Selena mixed rhythm and sound, which became her trademark.}}</ref>{{sfn|Parédez|2009|p=160}} Quintanilla III wrote increasingly Cumbia-influenced songs for ''Ven Conmigo'' (1990); Ramiro Burr of ''Billboard'' said Selena and her band had "evolved a rhythmic style that demonstrated its increasing prowess for catchy cumbias such as 'Baila Esta Cumbia' and the title track".<ref name=billboardguide>{{cite book|last1=Burr|first1=Ramiro|title=The Billboard guide to Tejano and regional Mexican music|date=1999|publisher=Billboard Books|isbn=0823076911|edition=1st|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9DPaAAAAMAAJ&dq=selena+baila+esta+cumbia|accessdate=October 10, 2014|quote=}}</ref> Italian essayist Gaetano Prampolini wrote that "Selena's voice projected a sonorous warmth and joyfulness" during her review of Selena's Cumbia recordings.{{sfn|Prampolini|2013|p=188}} In his review of the remix album ''[[Enamorada de Ti]]'' (2012), [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] wrote that Selena's songs were "rooted in the '90s and sound that way—but [''Enamorada de Ti''] is a relatively fresher repackaging of her music than many of her posthumous releases".<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|last1=Erlewine|first1=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|title=Enamorada de Ti (Album review)|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/enamorada-de-ti-mw0002315622|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref>

== Public image ==
Quintanilla, Jr. sought to maintain Selena's image clean and family-oriented.{{sfn|Peña|1999|p=206}} In 1989, she was offered sponsorship from beer companies but her father turned them down.<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/> Selena was often refused gigs at Tejano venues because she was a female singer in a male-dominated music scene.{{sfn|Pilchak|2005|p=39}} Manuel Peña wrote that after 1989, Selena's popularity increased and she became a sex icon following the release of her debut album.{{sfn|Peña|1999|p=206}} Charles Tatum said Selena drew most attention was for her "beauty, sexuality, and youthful impact on the Tejano music scene".{{sfn|Tatum|2013|p=1032}} Selena said she never wanted to record suggestive songs because of her upbringing and because her fan base consisted largely of young children, who regarded her as a role model.{{sfn|Parédez|2009|p=141}} She further commented on the question of her [[sexual appeal]] to men during her crossover attempt, asserting that she will "stay the same" and that her English-language recordings will refrain from foul language and sexual themes.{{sfn|Parédez|2009|p=141}} In 1997, [[María Celeste Arrarás]] wrote in her book about Selena's death that the singer was a "sweet and charismatic girl".{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|p=23}} According to Arrarás, Selena "trusted everyone"; she often went shopping alone, despite her father's concerns over her safety.{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|p=38}}

Betty Cortina of ''People'' magazine said Selena's provocative choice of clothing was an acceptable emulation of Janet Jackson and Madonna, and that she wore "sexy outfits that extenuated a body of a Latina woman".<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/>{{sfn|Foley|1997|p=16}} Cortina also stated that Selena had a "flamboyant style, an unbelievable body, curves and booty".<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/> Arrarás wrote that Selena "began wearing clothes designed to emphasize her curvaceous figure" and that she "never came across as cheap-simply sexy".{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|p=59}} She also said Selena's makeup regimen was not being "painted up or vulgar".{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|p=59}} Arrarás also noted Selena's "fun-loving stage manner" and said she was "playful onstage and off".{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|p=60}} Matt S. Meier wrote in his book ''The Mexican American Experience: An Encyclopedia'' (2010) that Selena exhibited "contagious energy" during her concerts and said she displayed "warmth, passion, and sexuality" while exuding a "down-to-earth persona of the wholesome young girl next door".{{sfn|Meier|2003|p=372}} Selena wore outfits that accented her physical attributes and was not afraid to wear outfits she liked,<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/> despite criticism from parents who thought Selena's choice of outfits were inappropriate for young girls, who began emulating Selena.{{sfn|Foley|1997|p=24}} Her views on public image in the fashion industry were bothersome; she said she was opposed to the image that all woman should be "rail-thin" and the notion that they must wear certain outfits and be "super-young to be beautiful".{{sfn|Tiscareño-Sato|2011}}

In the early 1990s, Selena began wearing decorative [[bustier]]s, spandex or tight pants, and attractive, unbuttoned jackets during her concerts.{{sfn|Foley|1997|p=24}} She was inspired by Paula Abdul, Janet Jackson, and Madonna.{{sfn|Foley|1997|p=24}} During a 1992 interview, Selena said her choice of clothing does not reflect her personality.<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/> [[NBC News]] called Selena's outfit "provocative".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reyes|first1=Paul|title=Still Missing Selena: Here Are 6 Reasons Why|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/still-missing-selena-here-are-6-reasons-why-n66031|accessdate=February 28, 2015|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=March 31, 2014|ref=image}}</ref> Because of her choices of outfits and dance moves, she was named by her fans as the "Mexican Madonna".{{sfn|Espinosa|2009|p=359}}{{sfn|Jones|2013|p=88}} According to Suzette, Selena often designed and sewed her own outfits backstage with her designers, moments before she was due on stage.<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/> Quintanilla, Jr. disapproved of Selena's outfits, but he later accepted it when Selena discussed about it being a fashion trend.<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/> Selena became an inactive member of the Jehovah's Witnesses due to her exotic clothing.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=167}} During the photo shoot for ''Entre a Mi Mundo'' (1992), a photographer remarked on the ways Selena's choice of clothing affected Quintanilla, Jr. tremendously; he often left sessions when Selena appeared in revealing outfits.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=117}} Selena was credited as the first women to change public perceptions of feminine beauty; a [[Feminist movement|feminist]], she blazed a trail for other female artists during her career.<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/>{{sfn|Jasinski|2012|p=457}}

Following Selena's death, some celebrities questioned her status as a role model among Hispanic women.  In her [[Corpus: A Home Movie About Selena|1999 documentary]] about the singer, filmmaker [[Lourdes Portillo]] expressed concerns whether Selena was a great role model to young women.<ref>{{cite web|title=Corpus: A Home Movie For Selena|url=http://www.pbs.org/pov/corpus/interview.php|website=''[[PBS]]''|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> Portillo believed Selena was sending the wrong message to young girls by dancing in clothing that suggested hypersexualization.{{sfn|Fregoso|2010|p=20}} American author [[Sandra Cisneros]] agreed with Portillo's assessment that Selena was "not a good role model to Latina women".{{sfn|Rebolledo|2005|p=126}} Media outlets also shared Portillo's views; they said the "fairy tale story" of Selena was one that her family would want to preserve, questioning Quintanilla, Jr.'s role for pushing an image that Selena had "never made mistakes" into the media, calling it "lies" and "not the real story".<ref>{{cite news|last=Persall|first=Steve|title=Selena becomes more saint than singer|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sptimes/access/17008498.html?dids=17008498:17008498&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT|accessdate=December 28, 2011|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|date=March 21, 1997|subscription=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McLane|first=Daisann|title=Santa Selena Does The Movie's "Official" Version of The Slain Tejano Singer's Life Show's The True Picture?|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/access/14705124.html?dids=14705124:14705124&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT|accessdate=December 28, 2011|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|date=March 18, 1997|subscription=yes}}</ref>

== Philanthropy ==
During her childhood, Selena helped organizations such as [[Toys for Tots]].{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=108}} She was active in the U.S. Latino community, visiting local schools to talk to students about the importance of education.{{sfn|Jones|2013|p=11}} At Fulmore Junior High School in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], she educated two hundred high school students about positive attitudes and setting life-goals in their adult lives.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=108}} Selena urged children to stay in school, and that alcohol and drugs will lead them nowhere in life.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=150}} She spent her free time helping her community. Selena performed in [[Washington D.C.]] to celebrate the forming of the [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]].{{sfn|Jones|2013|p=11}} Following the aftermath of [[Hurricane Andrew]], Selena helped victims in Florida by performing at a Houston benefit concert.{{sfn|Jones|2013|p=11}}{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=123}}

In August 1994, Selena hosted a charity baseball game to raise money for unspecified charities.{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|p=61}} She also donated her time to civic organizations such as [[Drug Abuse Resistance Education|D.A.R.E.]] and planned a fund raising concert to help [[AIDS]] patients.<ref name="biotexas"/> Selena participated with the Texas Prevention Partnership which was sponsored by the Texas Commission on Alcohol and Drug Abuse (Dep Corporation), which released an educational video that was sent to students for free.<ref name="biotexas"/> Her pro-education videos included "My Music" and "Selena Agrees". She was in the works for a [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]-[[Fort Worth, Texas]] [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America]] benefit concert.<ref name="biotexas"/>

In January 1995, Selena headlined the Teach the Children festival in San Antonio. The concert funded a non-profit program to provide school supplies to needy children.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=123}} Selena was a spokesperson for women in abusive relationships.{{sfn|Jones|2013|p=9}} She also helped out at homeless shelters.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=123}} According to the [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] television series ''[[Biography (TV series)|Biography]]'', Selena's fans were often minorities; she encouraged them to make the most of their lives.<ref name="Selena ''Biography''">{{Cite episode |title=Biography TV Series, Selena episode |episodelink= |series=Biography |serieslink= |credits= |network=The Biography Channel |station= |airdate=November 26, 2010 |season= |seriesno= |number= |minutes=60 }}</ref>

== Legacy and influence ==
{{see also|List of people influenced by Selena}}
Selena has been credited for helping redefine [[Latin music (genre)|Latin music]]{{sfn|Sickels|2013|p=482}} and its subgenres of Tejano,{{sfn|Parédez|2009|p=12}}{{sfn|Habell-Pallán|2002|p=121}} Cumbia, and Latin pop.{{sfn|Vargas|2012|p=188}}{{sfn|Segura|2007|p=477}} Selena broke barriers in the Latin music world.<ref name=mendoza>{{cite news|last1=Mendoza|first1=Madalyn|title=28 reasons Selena makes our hearts go 'bidi bidi bom bom'|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/entertainment/music-stage/article/Reasons-Selena-makes-our-hearts-go-bidi-bidi-bom-6103496.php|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref>{{sfn|Habell-Pallán|2002|p=122}}<ref name=zach>{{cite news|last1=Quaintance|first1=Zack|title=Remembering Selena|url=http://www.themonitor.com/news/local/remembering-selena/article_5429727a-8e9c-502d-bc2a-ff57de63b2a8.html|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]|date=March 31, 2010}}</ref> She is considered "one of the most significant Mexican American singers of the end of the twentieth century".{{sfn|Vargas|2012|p=183}} Selena also became one of the "most celebrated cultural products" of the United States-Mexico borderlands.{{sfn|Espinosa|2009|p=376}} Selena was called the "[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|Queen of Tejano music]]", and was described as "the most important and popular Tejano star of all time".{{sfn|Candelaria|2004|p=755}} Her death was "the most devastating loss" in Tejano music history, according to Zach Quaintance of the ''[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]''.<ref name=zach/> At the time of her death, Selena became one of the most widely known Mexican-American vocal artists{{sfn|Garcia|2002|p=220}}<ref name="Philip True">{{cite news|last=True|first=Philip|title=Selena's fans may turn her into folk hero|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAFE755B6E0302E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=October 10, 2011|newspaper=San Antonio Express-News|date=April 17, 1995|subscription=yes}}</ref> and the most popular Latin artist in the United States.<ref name="Philip True"/> She had a "cult-like" following among Hispanics.{{sfn|Espinosa|2009|p=377}}

Selena has been named one of the most influential Latin artists of all-time and has been credited for elevating a music genre into the [[mainstream]] market.<ref name="mainstream"/><ref name="influential"/> ''Latin Post'' called the singer "one of the most iconic artists in Latin American music history",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Akoukou Thompson|first1=Nicole|title=Selena, Shakira, Santana & More: The 100 Year History of Latin Music in the United States|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/5444/20140103/selena-shakira-santana-more-100-year-history-latin-music-united.htm|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=Latin Post|date=January 3, 2014}}</ref> while ''The New York Times'' called her "arguably the most important Latina musician in the country, on her way to becoming one of the most important, period."<ref name="soundname">{{cite news|last1=Pareles|first1=Jon|last2=Caramanica|first2=Jon|last3=Ratliff|first3=Ben|last4=Chinen|first4=Nate|last5=Holden|first5=Stephen|title=Wow! Every Song What's-His-Name Ever Recorded: Movies, Performing Arts/Weekend Desk|url=http://plp.ccc.commnet.edu:6012/nytimes/docview/812033801/AF8C82870FAE491FPQ/58?accountid=39924|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 26, 2010|issn=0362-4331|subscription=yes}}</ref> Selena became a household name in the United States and in Mexico following her death and became part of the American pop culture.<ref name="soundname"/>{{sfn|Mitchell|2007|p=387}} She became more popular in death than when she was alive.{{sfn|Espinosa|2009|p=364}} After her death, her popularity among the Hispanic population was compared to those of [[Marilyn Monroe]] and Madonna in Anglo-American culture.{{sfn|Espinosa|2009|p=372}} According to author Carlota Caulfield, Selena was "one of the most popular Latina singers of the 1990s".{{sfn|Caulfield|2007|p=223}} Selena's popularity was drawn in by the LGBT community and minority groups in the United States.{{sfn|Vargas|2012|p=185}} The popularity of Tejano music waned after her death, and as of 2015, has not recovered.{{sfn|Mcdonald|2010|p=364}}<ref name=pop>{{cite news|last1=Platenburg|first1=Gheni|title=Popularity of Tejano music wanes; conjunto, other Regional Mexican music takes over|url=http://www.themonitor.com/entertainment/article_87e273fd-071f-505e-b805-654d8aca0ceb.html|accessdate=January 31, 2015|work=[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]|date=October 17, 2011}}</ref> John Lannert of ''Billboard'' said in an interview with ''Biography'' in 2007 that when Selena died the "Tejano market died with her".<ref name="Selena ''Biography''"/>

''[[Dreaming of You (album)|Dreaming of You]]'', the crossover album Selena had been working on at the time of her death, was released in July 1995. It sold 175,000 copies on the day of its release in the U.S.{{mdash}}a then-record for a female vocalist{{mdash}}and sold 331,000 copies its first week.<ref name="copiessold">{{cite news |title=No. 1 start for Selena's `Dreaming' |url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/19370751.html?dids=19370751:19370751&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+27%2C+1995&author=Edna+Gundersen&pub=USA+TODAY+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=No.+1+start+for+Selena's+`Dreaming'&pqatl=google |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=July 27, 1995 |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Selena's Popularity Grows|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0xYhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KHUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1284,3326132&dq=selena+dreaming+of+you&hl=en|accessdate=April 28, 2013|newspaper=[[The Hour (newspaper)|The Hour]]|date=March 24, 2004}}</ref> Selena became the third female artist to sell over 300,000 units in one week, after Janet Jackson and [[Mariah Carey]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=Selling like a dream&nbsp;— Selena CD outpaces previous top sellers|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAFE76A19B821FF&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=January 19, 2013|newspaper=San Antonio Express-News|date=July 25, 1995|quote="With first-week sales of "Dreaming of You" at about 400,000-plus, Selena has become the fastest-selling female artist in music history. Final full-week sales figures will not be available until later this week, but on Monday EMI Latin officials estimated Selena's sales at more than 400,000, which puts the late singer ahead of other previous top sellers including: Janet Jackson, "Janet," 350,000; Mariah Carey[...]"|subscription=yes}}</ref> It debuted at number one on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, becoming the first album by a Hispanic artist to do so.<ref name="Billboard">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1179058/allmusiccom-folding-into-allrovicom-for-one-stop-entertainment-shop |title=AllMusic.com Folding Into AllRovi.com for One-Stop Entertainment Shop |last=Bruno |first=Anthony |date=February 28, 2011 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Marrero|first=Letisha|title=Ritmo Roundup|journal=Vibe|date=November 2003|volume=13|issue=13|page=172|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_yYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA122|accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=Upcoming Selena Tribute|journal=Billboard|date=March 26, 2005|volume=117|issue=13|page=56|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oxQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA55|accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref> ''Dreaming of You'' helped Selena to become the first solo artist to debut a posthumous album at number one.<ref name=recordbreak>{{cite journal|last=Lannert|first=John|title=Latin Notas|journal=Billboard|date=August 5, 1995|volume=107|issue=31|url=https://books.google.com/booksid=xwsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA1&dq=Selena+Dreaming+of+you+song&hl=en&sa=X&ei=oIqfUdOxKIbT0gHykYDwBQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwATjSAQ#v=onepage&q=Selena%20Dreaming%20of%20you%20song&f=false|accessdate=May 25, 2013}}</ref> The recording was among the top-ten best-selling debuts for a musician, and was the best-selling debut by a female act.<ref name="The Selena Phenomenon">{{cite journal|last=Lannert|first=John|title=The Selena Phenomenon|journal=Billboard|date=September 2, 1995|volume=107|issue=35|page=120|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xw0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA41|accessdate=December 2, 2011}}</ref> ''Dreaming of You'' joined five of Selena's studio albums on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart simultaneously, making Selena the first female artist in ''Billboard'' history to do so.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lannert|first=John|title=A Retrospective|journal=Billboard|date=June 10, 1995|volume=107|issue=23|page=112|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0QsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA62&dq=Selena+Entre+a+Mi+Mundo#v=onepage&q=Selena%20Entre%20a%20Mi%20Mundo&f=false|accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref> The album was certified 35x platinum by the RIAA, for shipping more than 3.5 million copies in the U.S. alone.<ref name="RIAA"/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Awards Show|journal=Billboard|date=May 4, 1996|volume=108|issue=18|page=122|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9gsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA46&dq=Selena+Dreaming+of+You#v=onepage&q=Selena%20Dreaming%20of%20You&f=false|accessdate=December 7, 2011|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> As of 2015, the recording has sold five million copies worldwide, becoming the best-selling Latin album of all-time in the United States.<ref name="fiesta">{{cite news|last1=Guerra|first1=Joey|title=Selena to be honored at Fiesta de la Flor in Corpus Christi|url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/texas/article/Selena-to-be-honored-at-Fiesta-de-la-Flor-in-6047273.php|accessdate=March 9, 2015|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|publisher=Jack Sweeney|date=January 28, 2015}}</ref> In 2008, [[Joey Guerra]] of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' said its lead single, "[[I Could Fall in Love]]", had "made the Tejano goddess a posthumous crossover star".<ref name="houston">{{cite news|last=Guerra|first=Joey|title=Gloria Estefan in a league of her own 'Person of the Year' a longtime inspiration|url=http://www.chron.com/life/article/Gloria-Estefan-in-a-league-of-her-own-1778206.php|accessdate=June 26, 2012|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=October 30, 2008}}</ref> Her death was believed to have sparked an interest in Latin music by people who were unaware of its existence.{{sfn|Jones|2000|p=81}}{{sfn|Sickels|2013|p=482}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lannert|first1=John|title=Latin Music Has New Challenges At Anglo Market|journal=Billboard|date=July 29, 1995|volume=107|issue=30|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yQsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA1&lpg=PA1&dq=Selena+death+interest+in+Latin+music+-gomez,+-hill,+-miley#v=onepage&q=Selena%20death%20interest%20in%20Latin%20music%20-gomez%2C%20-hill%2C%20-miley&f=false|accessdate=March 26, 2015}}</ref> It was also believed her death "open[ed] the doors" to other Latin musicians such as [[Jennifer Lopez]],{{sfn|Jones|2000|p=82}} [[Ricky Martin]], and [[Shakira]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Guerra|first1=Joey|title=A tribute to Selena among this year's QFest offerings|url=http://www.chron.com/life/article/A-tribute-to-Selena-among-this-year-s-QFest-3732004.php|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=July 24, 2012}}</ref>

In the same year, the [[United States Social Security Administration]] ranked the name Selena one of the 100 most popular names for newborn girls.<ref name=mysan>{{cite news|last1=Renter|first1=Melissa|title=The legacy of Selena|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/sacultura/conexion/article/The-legacy-of-Selena-795056.php|accessdate=January 31, 2015|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=March 25, 2010}}</ref> In December 1999, Selena was named the "top Latin artist of the '90s" and "Best selling Latin artist of the decade" by ''Billboard'' for her fourteen top-ten singles in the Top Latin Songs chart, including seven number-one hits.<ref name="selena">{{Cite journal| last = Mayfield| first = Geoff| date = December 25, 1999| title = Totally '90s: Diary of a Decade| journal = Billboard| volume = 111| issue = 52| issn = 0006-2510| page = YE–16–18| url = https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=9w0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA66| accessdate = March 30, 2010}}</ref> She was the best-selling Latin female singer of the 1990s in the U.S. and Mexico.<ref name=postamerican>{{cite news|title=The American Dream|url=https://web.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?vid=6&sid=f4f1bd15-039d-4a97-9ccf-d68edc08d4f3%40sessionmgr4005&hid=4209&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZSZzY29wZT1zaXRl#db=n5h&AN=EVP0101294061-FSELEN-FE|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[The Dominion Post (Morgantown)|The Dominion Post]]|date=January 29, 2001|subscription=yes}}</ref> Selena was named "Best Female Vocalist of the '80s" and "Best Female Vocalist of the '90s" at the [[2010 Tejano Music Awards]].<ref name="TMAs"/>

=== Posthumous film and honors ===
In the months following her death, a number of honors and tributes were erected. Several proposals were made, such as renaming streets, public parks, food products,{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|p=33}} and auditoriums.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=318}} Two months later, a tribute was held at the 1995 Lo Nuestro Awards.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Chito de la Torre|title=En Vivo: Premio Lo Nuestro|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-52976134.html|accessdate=April 13, 2015|work=[[La Prensa de San Antonio]]|publisher=Duran Duran Industries|date=May 12, 1995|language=Spanish|subscription=yes}}</ref> The Spirit of Hope Award was created in Selena's honor in 1996;<ref>{{cite journal|title=Billboard's Magazine 1996 Latin Music Awards Scheduled For May 1 At The Historical Gusman Center for Performing Arts|journal=Billboard|date=March 2, 1996|volume=108|issue=9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Og8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=Selena+Billboard+Music+Awards#v=onepage&q=Selena%20Billboard%20Music%20Awards&f=false|accessdate=September 11, 2012|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> it was awarded to Latin artists who participated in humanitarian and civic causes.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Songwriters Speak|journal=Billboard|date=April 29, 2006|volume=118|issue=17|url=https://books.google.com/?id=USkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA30&lpg=RA1-PA30&dq=The+Spirit+of+Hope+Award+was+created+in+Selena's+honor+for+her#v=onepage&q=The%20Spirit%20of%20Hope%20Award%20was%20created%20in%20Selena's%20honor%20for%20her&f=false|accessdate=September 11, 2012|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> On March 16, 2011, the [[United States Postal Service]] released a "Latin Legends" memorial stamp to honor Selena, [[Carlos Gardel]], [[Tito Puente]], Celia Cruz, and [[Carmen Miranda]].<ref name="stamps">{{cite web |url=http://newstaco.com/2011/01/18/selena-celia-cruz-tito-puente-in-u-s-postal-stamp-form/ |title=Selena, Celia Cruz, Tito Puente In U.S. Postal Stamp Form |author=Sara Inés Calderón |date=January 18, 2011 |publisher=NewsTaco |accessdate=March 7, 2011}}</ref> In February 2014, the Albany, NY ''[[Times Union (Albany)|Times Union]]'' named her one of "100 Coolest Americans in History".<ref name=americanhistory>{{cite news|title=The 100 coolest Americans in history|url=http://www.timesunion.com/entertainment/article/The-100-coolest-Americans-in-history-5252418.php#photo-5914364|accessdate=February 22, 2014|newspaper=[[Times Union (Albany)|Times Union]]|date=February 20, 2014}}</ref> In 1997 Selena was commemorated with a museum and a life-size [[bronze sculpture|bronze statue]] in Corpus Christi, which are visited by hundreds of fans each week.{{sfn|Parédez|2009|p=259}}

In 1995, Selena was inducted into the [[Billboard Latin Music Hall of Fame|''Billboard'' Latin Music Hall of Fame]],<ref name="lmba1995">{{cite journal| last = Lannert| first = John| date = June 10, 1995| title = Beloved Selena Enters The Latin Music Hall of Fame| journal = Billboard| volume = 107| issue = 23| page = 58| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=0QsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA58| accessdate = April 11, 2014}}</ref> the [[Hard Rock Cafe]]'s Hall of Fame,{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|p=34}} and the South Texas Music Hall of Fame.{{sfn|Jasinski|2012}} In 2001 she was inducted into the Tejano Music Hall of Fame.{{sfn|Meier|2003|p=372}} The singer received a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moll-Ramirez|first1=Victoria|title=Late Singer Selena Among Latinos to Get Star on Hollywood Walk of Fame|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/late-singer-selena-among-latinos-get-star-hollywood-walk-fame-n600951|website=''NBC News''|accessdate=6 July 2016}}</ref> She was named one of the 20 most influential Texans of all time by author Laurie Jasinski.{{sfn|Jasinski|2012}} She was ranked fifth of the "100 most influential Latin musicians of the 20th century" according to the ''[[Orange County Register]]''.<ref name=mostinfluential>{{cite news|last1=Wener|first1=Ben|last2=Chang|first2=Daniel|last3=Eddy|first3=Steve|last4=Darling|first4=Cary|title=Choosing the 100 most influential Latin musicians of the 20th century|url=https://web.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?vid=9&sid=f4f1bd15-039d-4a97-9ccf-d68edc08d4f3%40sessionmgr4005&hid=4209&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZSZzY29wZT1zaXRl#db=n5h&AN=4N52460169164215|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[Orange County Register]]|date=December 30, 1999|subscription=yes}}</ref> The singer has been given many epithets by media outlets, including the "Queen of Latin music",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://natedsanders.com/queen-of-latin-music,-selenas-official-1994-tejan-lot24865.aspx|title=Queen of Latin Music, Selena's Official 1994 Tejano Music Award for Album of the Year – Just a Year Before Her Tragic Death|work=Nate D. Sanders Auctions|publisher=natedsanders.com/|date=January 30, 2014|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> the "Queen of Cumbia",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Guerra|first1=Joey|title=Happy birthday, Selena: 'Our cumbia queen'|url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/life/article/Happy-birthday-Selena-Our-cumbia-queen-5404320.php#/0|accessdate=April 7, 2015|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=April 15, 2014}}</ref> the "Chicana Elvis",<ref name=lopezsantafe>{{cite news|last1=Lopez|first1=Antonio|title=Selena, Selena: We Hardly Knew You|url=https://web.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?vid=3&sid=f4f1bd15-039d-4a97-9ccf-d68edc08d4f3%40sessionmgr4005&hid=4209&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZSZzY29wZT1zaXRl#db=n5h&AN=378860585|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[Santa Fe New Mexican]]|date=April 6, 1997|subscription=yes}}</ref> the "Queen of hybrid pop culture", the "Hispanic Marilyn Monroe",<ref name=dreamingrep/> the "[[Tupac Shakur]] of Latin music",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Patrick|title=Michael Jackson joins a Posthumous Hot 100|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/06/24/posthumous-albums-michael-jackson-notorious-big-selena-beatles-janis-joplin/11210697/|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[USA Today]]|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref> the "Corpus Christi queen",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Salians|first1=Rebecca|title=Fake story reporting Selena's killer leaving prison early nearly 'breaks the Internet' in S. Texas|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local/article/Fake-story-stating-Selena-s-killer-will-leave-5945118.php|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> and the "people's princess".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ybarra|first1=Rose|title=Family perseveres after Selenas death|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/local/article_2df8d8ab-2643-52ed-8f92-b67570abe73f.html|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[The Brownsville Herald]]|date=April 1, 2005}}</ref>{{sfn|Jones|2000|p=87}} Media have compared Selena's fashion sense to that of  Madonna more times than any other celebrity.{{sfn|Parédez|2009|p=116}}<ref name="victoria"/><ref name=NewYorkTimes/><ref>{{cite web|title=Selena Murder Trial Begins Monday|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/504751/selena-murder-trial-begins-monday/|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=March 26, 2015}}</ref>

In 1995, Mexican actress [[Salma Hayek]] was chosen to play the role of Selena in a biopic film produced by the Quintanilla family and [[Warner Bros.]]<ref>{{cite journal|title=Selena to Big Screen|journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=September 8, 1995|issue=291|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,298633,00.html|accessdate=28 December 2011}}</ref> Hayek turned the role down; she said she felt it was "too early" to base a movie on Selena and that it would be emotional because Selena's death was still being covered on U.S. television.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pearlman|first=Cindy|title=Selena: the story behind the legend|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CSTB&p_theme=cstb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB422F6A50DAE55&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10|accessdate=December 28, 2011|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|date=March 16, 1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Longsdorf|first=Amy|title=Director Aims For Truth About Selena's Life|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/mcall/access/14351783.html?dids=14351783:14351783&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT|accessdate=December 28, 2011|newspaper=The Morning Call|date=March 21, 1997}}</ref> Puerto Rican-American actress Jennifer Lopez replaced Hayek, which drew criticism because of Lopez' Puerto-Rican ancestry.{{sfn|Tracy|2008|p=53}} Over 21,000 people auditioned for the title role, becoming the second largest audition since the search for [[Scarlett O'Hara]] in ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone With the Wind]]'' (1939).{{sfn|Arrarás|1997|p=31}}<ref name=selenamoviecast>{{cite news|last1=Puente|first1=Teresa|title=The Unforeseen Legacy Of Selena Quintanilla Perez|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-03-30/news/9703300300_1_selena-quintanilla-perez-people-en-espanol-latinas|accessdate=March 26, 2015|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=March 30, 1997}}</ref> [[Gregory Nava]] directed for the film, which was released on March 21, 1997. After seeing Lopez' performance in it, fans changed their views on her. ''Selena'' opened in 1,850 theaters worldwide and grossed $11,615,722, making it the second-highest-grossing film debut that week.<ref name=gross>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1997/SELEN.php |title=Selena&nbsp;– Box Office Data, News, Cast Information |work=The Numbers |accessdate=January 22, 2012}}</ref> With a production budget of $20 million, the film grossed $35 million in the U.S.<ref name=gross/> The film was a commercial and critical success<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/1073427-selena |title=Selena |work=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=November 29, 2011}}</ref> and is often cited by critics as Lopez' [[breakthrough role]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9PRoPX3DIwgC&pg=PA387&lpg=PA387&dq=selena+jennifer+lopez+breakout#v=onepage&q=selena%20jennifer%20lopez%20breakout&f=false|title=Girl Culture: An Encyclopedia|page=387|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |date=December 30, 2007 |accessdate=November 27, 2011|isbn=978-0-313-08444-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://latina.com/breakout-roles-jennifer-lopez |title=Breakout Roles: Jennifer Lopez |website=Latina |date=December 19, 2011 |accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> Lopez rose into pop culture, for which the film's success was credited.{{sfn|Vargas|2012|p=53}}

In 1999, a Broadway-bound musical titled ''Selena'' was scheduled to premiere in San Antonio in March 2000 to commemorate the fifth anniversary of her murder. Broadway producers [[Tom Quinn (actor)|Tom Quinn]], [[Jerry Frankel (producer)|Jerry Frankel]], [[Peter Fitzgerald (actor)|Peter Fitzgerald]], and [[Michael Vega]] staged the musical,<ref name="elmusical">{{cite news |title=Quién es Quién en el Teatro en México: Angie Vega |first=Clemente|last=Sanchez |url=http://mexico.broadwayworld.com/article/Quin-es-Quin-en-el-Teatro-en-Mxico-Angie-Vega-20110422 |newspaper=Broadway World.com. |date=April 22, 2011 |accessdate=May 31, 2011}}</ref> and Edward Gallardo wrote the show's book and lyrics. [[Fernando Rivas]] composed the show's songs. In 2000, ''[[Selena Forever]]'' was first produced; the show embarked on a 30-city U.S. tour with a budget of over US$2&nbsp;million.<ref name="elmusical"/> After a national casting call, producers chose [[Veronica (singer)|Veronica Vasquez]] to portray Selena; Vasquez alternated in the role with Rebecca Valdez.<ref name=musical>{{cite news|title=Selena musical to be staged here in April|url=http://www.caller2.com/2000/february/03/today/local_ne/7687.html|accessdate=October 25, 2011|newspaper=Corpus Christi Caller Times|date=February 3, 2000}}</ref> The musical previewed on March 21, and opened on March 23 at the San Antonio Municipal Auditorium.<ref name=enjoy>{{cite news|title=Crowds enjoy preview of 'Selena Forever'|url=http://www.caller2.com/2000/march/22/today/local_ne/3224.html|accessdate=October 25, 2011|newspaper=Corpus Christi Caller Times|date=March 22, 2000}}</ref>

Selena's family and her former band, Los Dinos, held a tribute concert on April 7, 2005, a week after the 10th anniversary of her murder. The concert, titled ''[[Selena ¡VIVE!]]'', was broadcast live on [[Univision]] and achieved a 35.9 [[Nielsen ratings|household rating]]. It was the highest-rated and most-viewed Spanish-language television special in the history of American television. The special was also the number-one program in any language among adults ages 18 to 34 in Los Angeles, Chicago, and San Francisco; it tied for first in New York, beating that night's episode of [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s reality show ''[[American Idol]]''.<ref name="billboardvive">{{cite news|title=Selena's Appeal Still Strong |first=Leila|last=Cobo |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BBUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA21|newspaper=Billboard |date=April 23, 2005 |accessdate=October 18, 2011}}</ref> Among Hispanic viewers, ''Selena ¡VIVE!'' outperformed [[Super Bowl XLV]] and the telenovela ''[[Soy tu dueña]]'' during the "most-watched NFL season ever among Hispanics".<ref>{{cite web|last=Seidman|first=Robert|title=Super Bowl XLV Most-Watched Show in U.S. TV History Among Hispanic Viewers; Tops World Cup Final|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/02/08/super-bowl-xlv-most-watched-show-in-u-s-tv-history-among-hispanic-viewers-tops-world-cup-final/81887/|work=TVbythenumbers|publisher=Zap2it|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gorman|first=Bill|title=NFL 2010 Hispanic TV Recap, Most-Watched NFL Season Ever Among Hispanics|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/02/16/nfl-2010-hispanic-tv-recap-most-watched-nfl-season-ever-among-hispanics/82972/|work=TVbythenumbers|publisher=Zap2it|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref>

In January 2015, it was announced that a two-day annual event called [[Fiesta de la Flor]] would be held in Corpus Christi for Selena by the Corpus Christi Visitors Bureau. Musical acts for the first annual event included [[Kumbia All-Starz]], Chris Pérez, [[Los Lobos]], Jay Perez, [[Little Joe (singer)|Little Joe y la Familia]], [[Los Palominos]], Stefani Montiel of [[Las 3 Divas]], [[Girl in a Coma]]'s Nina Diaz, Las Fenix, and previous ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]'' competitor [[The Voice (U.S. season 6)|Clarissa Serna]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nunez|first1=Alana|title=Selena Is Getting Her Own Festival to Honor the 20th Anniversary of Her Death|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/celebs/news/a35794/selena-twentieth-anniversary/|website=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Flores|first1=Adofo|title=Mexican-American Icon Selena Will Be Honored In Texas Festival 20 Years After Her Death|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/adolfoflores/texas-festival-to-honor-selena-on-20th-anniversary-of-her-de#.lsV8Pz00k|website=''[[BuzzFeed]]''|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Guerra|first1=Joey|title=Tejano star Selena to be honored at Fiesta de la Flor|url=http://www.chron.com/entertainment/music/article/Tejano-star-Selena-to-be-honored-at-Fiesta-de-la-6045907.php|accessdate=March 10, 2015|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=January 28, 2015}}</ref> The event raised $13 million with an attendance of 52,000 people with 72% of whom lived outside of Corpus Christi. The event sparked interest from people in 35 states and five different countries including Mexico, Brazil, and Ecuador.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Economic Impact of the Fiesta de la Flor Festival|url=http://www.kiiitv.com/story/28912371/the-economic-impact-of-the-fiesta-de-la-flor-festival|accessdate=April 29, 2015|work=[[KIII|KIII TV]]|date=April 27, 2015}}</ref>

